]]'s ex-wife from the [[Doctor Who (series 3)|third series]] and [[Doctor Who (2008\u20132010 specials)|2008\u20132010 specials]] of the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' revival series\n* [[Lucy Stillman]], recurring character in ''[[Assassin's Creed]]''\n* [[Lucy Loud]], in the TV series ''[[The Loud House]]''\n* Lucy Carlyle, main character in the [[The Screaming Staircase|Lockwood and Co.]] series by [[Jonathan Stroud]]\n* Lucy Mills, a main character in [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC's]] ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''\n* Lucy Simion, a character from [[The Amazing World of Gumball]]\n* Lucy, a character from item number \"Jokae\" portrayed by [[Mounu Roy]] from film [[K.G.F: Chapter 1]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Luci]]\n* [[Lusi (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Lucie]]\n* [[Lucey]]\n* [[Lucy (Australopithecus)]], fossil\n* [[Lucia (disambiguation)]]\n* the star [[BPM 37093]], nicknamed \"Lucy\"\n* [[Lucy the elephant]], tourist attraction in Margate, New Jersey\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:English feminine given names]]\n[[Category:French feminine given names]]\n", "name_user": "Googgoollman7777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePeople:Added glamour for Lucy Pinder.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucy"}
{"title_page": "SpaceX CRS-1", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = SpaceX CRS-1\n| image                 = SpaceX CRS-1 approaches ISS-cropped.jpg\n| image_caption         = The Dragon CRS-1 is seen approaching the ISS.\n| insignia              = SpaceX CRS-1 Patch.png\n| insignia_caption      = NASA SpX-1 mission patch\n\n| mission_type          = [[International Space Station|ISS]] resupply\n| operator              = [[NASA]]\n| COSPAR_ID             = 2012-054A\n| SATCAT                = 38846\n| mission_duration      = {{time interval|8 October 2012 00:34:07|28 October 2012 19:22|show=dhm|sep=,}}\n\n| spacecraft            = Dragon C103\n| spacecraft_type       = [[SpaceX Dragon#Dragon CRS|Dragon CRS]]\n| manufacturer          = [[SpaceX]]\n| dry_mass              = \n| launch_mass           = \n\n| launch_date           = 8 October 2012<br/>00:34:07 UTC <ref name=\"NASA EH\"/><ref name=NASAsept20/>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Falcon 9]] v1.0\n| launch_site           = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 40|SLC-40]] <ref name=\"SpaceX Launch Manifest\"/><ref name=\"NASA Launch Schedule\"/>\n| launch_contractor     = [[SpaceX]]\n| disposal_type         = Recovered\n| landing_date          = {{end-date|28 October 2012, 19:22|timezone=yes}} UTC <ref name=ClarkOct28/>\n| landing_site          = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n\n| orbit_epoch           = 8 October 2012\n| orbit_reference       = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime          = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis       = \n| orbit_apoapsis        = \n| orbit_inclination     = 51.6\u00b0\n| orbit_period          = \n| apsis                 = gee\n\n| docking               = \n {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target     = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n   | docking_type       = berth\n   | docking_port       = [[Harmony (ISS module)|Harmony]]\n   | capture_date       = 10 October 2012, 10:56 UTC\n   | docking_date       = 10 October 2012, 13:03 UTC <ref name=SPACENOW10/>\n   | undocking_date     = 28 October 2012, 11:19 UTC <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aviationweek.com/Blogs.aspx?plckBlogId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385&plckPostId=Blog%3A04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385Post%3A4cbd3925-a48e-4c00-a26e-1e90c4466f96|title=SpaceX Dragon CRS-1 Capsule Departs Space Station|last=Carreau|first=Mark|date=28 October 2012|publisher=Aviation Week|accessdate=30 October 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006200230/http://www.aviationweek.com/Blogs.aspx?plckBlogId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385|archivedate=6 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n   | release_date       = 28 October 2012, 13:29 UTC\n   | time_docked        = 17 days 22 hours 16 minutes\n }}\n\n| cargo_mass            = 400 kg\n| cargo_mass_press      = 400 kg\n| cargo_mass_unpress    = \n| cargo_mass_fuel       = \n| cargo_mass_gas        = \n| cargo_mass_water      = \n\n| programme             = [[Commercial Resupply Services]]\n| previous_mission      = [[Dragon C2+]]\n| next_mission          = [[SpaceX CRS-2]]\n}}\n\n'''SpaceX CRS-1''', also known as '''SpX-1''',<ref name=HARTMAN/> was the third flight for [[SpaceX|Space Exploration Technologies Corporation's]] (SpaceX) uncrewed [[SpaceX Dragon|Dragon]] [[Comparison of space station cargo vehicles|cargo spacecraft]], the fourth overall flight for the company's two-stage [[Falcon 9]] launch vehicle, and the first SpaceX operational mission under their [[Commercial Resupply Services]] contract with [[NASA]]. The launch occurred on 8 October 2012 at 00:34:07 UTC.<ref name=\"NASA EH\"/><ref name=NASAsept20/><ref name=wsj20120707-8:38pm>{{Cite news|last=Pasztor|first=Andy|title=SpaceX Launches Cargo Flight to Space Station|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443482404578043100196815928|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Spaceflight Now\"/>\n\n== History ==\nIn May 2012, it was reported that the Falcon 9 had been transported to [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]].<ref name=\"Clark 18 May 2012\"/> The Dragon CRS-1 arrived on 14 August 2012.<ref name=\"Clark 24 August 2012\"/> On 31 August 2012, a [[wet dress rehearsal]] (WDR) was completed for the Falcon 9, and on 29 September a static fire test was completed; both of these tests were completed without the Dragon capsule attached to the launch vehicle stack.<ref name=AugustChris/><ref name=Sept29/> The mission passed its Launch Readiness Review (LRR) on 5 October 2012.<ref name=\"Spaceflight Now\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121005preview/|title=Commercial resupply of space station blasts off Sunday|publisher=SpaceFlightNow|date=5 October 2012|accessdate=6 October 2012|last=Clark |first=Stephen}}</ref>\n\nThe launch occurred on 8 October 2012 at 00:34:07 UTC and successfully placed the Dragon spacecraft into the proper orbit for arriving at the International Space Station with cargo resupply several days later. During the launch, one of the nine engines suffered a sudden loss of pressure 79 seconds into the flight, and an immediate early shutdown of that engine occurred; debris could be seen in the telescopic video of the night launch. The remaining eight engines fired for a longer period of time and the flight control software adjusted the trajectory to insert Dragon into a near-flawless [[low-Earth orbit|orbit]].<ref name=tsr20121008>{{cite news|last=Foust|first=Jeff|title=Commercial spaceflight gets down to business|url=http://thespacereview.com/article/2168/1|accessdate=10 October 2012|newspaper=The Space Review |date=8 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Mission timeline ==\n\n=== Flight day 1, launch (8 October) ===\n[[File:SpaceX CRS-1 launch cropped.jpg|thumb|left|The SpaceX CRS-1 Falcon 9 launches on 8 October 2012.]]\n\nThe mission plan, as published by NASA before the mission, called for the Falcon 9 to reach [[supersonic speed]] at 70 seconds after liftoff, and pass through the area of maximum aerodynamic pressure, \"[[max Q]]\" \u2014 the point when mechanical stress on the rocket peaks due to a combination of the rocket's velocity and resistance created by the Earth's atmosphere \u2014 10 seconds later. The plan called for two of the first-stage engines to shut down to reduce the rocket's acceleration at approximately 2 minutes 30 seconds into the flight when the Falcon 9 would nominally be {{convert|90|km|mi}} high and traveling at 10 times the speed of sound. The remaining engines were planned to cut off shortly after\u2014an event known as main-engine cutoff (MECO). Five seconds after MECO, the first and second stages separate. Seven seconds later, the second stage's single Merlin vacuum engine was projected to ignite to begin a 6-minute, 14-second burn to put Dragon into [[low-Earth orbit]]. Forty seconds after second-stage ignition, Dragon's protective nose cone, which covers Dragon's berthing mechanism, was planned to be jettisoned. At the 9-minute, 14-second mark after launch, the second-stage engine was scheduled to cut off (SECO). Thirty-five seconds later, Dragon was planned to separate from Falcon 9's second stage and reach its preliminary orbit. The dragon would, per plan, then deploy its solar arrays and open its guidance and navigation control (GNC) bay door which holds the sensors necessary for rendezvous and Dragon's [[Power Data Grapple Fixture|grapple fixture]].<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\n=== Flight day 2 (9 October) ===\nThe mission plan called for the Dragon spacecraft to perform a coelliptic burn that would place it in a circular [[coelliptic orbit]].<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\n=== Flight day 3 (10 October) ===\nAs Dragon chased the [[International Space Station]], the spacecraft established UHF communication using its COTS Ultra-high-frequency Communication Unit (CUCU). Also, using the crew command panel (CCP) onboard the station, the expedition crew monitored the approach. This ability for the crew to send commands to Dragon is important during the rendezvous and departure phases of the mission.<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\nDuring the final approach to the station, a go/no-go was performed by [[Christopher C. Kraft Jr. Mission Control Center#FCR 1 (2006-present)|Mission Control Houston]] and the SpaceX team in Hawthorne to allow Dragon to perform another engine burn that brought it {{convert|250|m|ft}} from the station. At this distance, Dragon began using its close-range guidance systems, composed of [[LIDAR]] and thermal imagers. These systems confirmed that Dragon's position and velocity are accurate by comparing the LIDAR image that Dragon receives against Dragon's thermal imagers. The Dragon flight control team in Hawthorne, with assistance from the NASA flight control team at the Johnson Space Center's International Space Station Flight Control Room, commanded the spacecraft to approach the station from its hold position. After another go/no-go was performed by the Houston and Hawthorne teams, Dragon was permitted to enter the Keep-Out Sphere (KOS), an imaginary sphere drawn {{convert|200|m|ft}} around the station that reduces the risk of collision. Dragon proceeded to a position {{convert|30|m|ft}} from the station and was automatically held. Another go/no-go was completed. Then Dragon proceeded to the {{convert|10|m|ft}} position \u2014 the capture point. A final go/no-go was performed, and the Mission Control Houston team notified the crew they were going for the capture of Dragon.<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\nAt that point, Expedition 33 crewmember [[Akihiko Hoshide]] of the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency used the station's {{convert|17.6|m|ft}} robotic arm, known as [[Mobile Servicing System#Canadarm2 |Canadarm2]], reached for and grappled the Dragon spacecraft at 10:56 UTC.<ref name=SPACENOW10/> Hoshide, with the help of Expedition 33 Commander [[Sunita Williams]] of NASA, guided Dragon to the Earth-facing side of the station's [[Harmony module]]. Williams and Hoshide swapped places and Williams gently berthed Dragon to Harmony's [[Common Berthing Mechanism]] at 13:03 UTC.<ref name=SPACENOW10/>\n\nThe opening of the hatch between Dragon and the Harmony module, which was originally not scheduled to occur until 11 October, was moved up and occurred at 17:40 UTC.<ref name=SPACENOW10/>\n\n=== Remainder of mission (11 to 28 October) ===\n[[File:SpX CRS-1 berthed - cropped.jpg|thumb|right|A Dragon as seen from [[Cupola (ISS module)|Cupola]] on 14 October 2012.]]\n\nOver a period of two and a half weeks, the ISS crew unloaded Dragon's payload and reloaded it with cargo for return to Earth.<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>{{Failed verification|date=November 2012}}<!-- a source from before the flight does not confirm that the planned event became a past-tense historical fact; needs a better source, or the prose needs to speak to the mission plan as outlined in the presskit -->\n\nAfter its mission at the orbital laboratory was completed, newly arrived Expedition 33 Flight Engineer [[Kevin A. Ford|Kevin Ford]] used the Canadarm2 robotic arm to detach Dragon from Harmony, maneuver it out to the 15-meter (50-foot) release point, and release the vehicle. Dragon then performed a series of three burns to place it on a trajectory away from the station. Approximately six hours after Dragon departed the station, it conducted a deorbit burn, which lasted up to 10 minutes. Dragon's trunk, which contains its solar arrays, was then jettisoned.<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>{{Failed verification|date=November 2012}}<!-- a source from before the flight does not confirm that the planned event became a past-tense historical fact; needs a better source, or the prose needs to speak to the mission plan as outlined in the presskit -->\n[[File:SpX-1 Dragon at port.1.jpg|thumb|left|The SpX-1 capsule seen back at port on 30 October 2012]]\nThe landing was controlled by automatic firing of its [[Draco (rocket engine family)#Draco|Draco]] thrusters during [[Atmospheric entry|reentry]].{{Failed verification|date=November 2012}}<!-- a source from before the flight does not confirm that the planned event became a past-tense historical fact; needs a better source, or the prose needs to speak to the mission plan as outlined in the presskit --> In a carefully timed sequence of events, dual [[drogue parachute]]s deploy at an altitude of {{convert|13700|m|ft|abbr=on}} to stabilize and slow the spacecraft. Full deployment of the drogues triggers the release of the three main parachutes, each 35 meters (116 feet) in diameter, at about {{convert|3000|m|ft|abbr=on}}. While the drogues detach from the spacecraft, the main parachutes further slow the spacecraft's descent to approximately {{convert|4.8|to|5.4|m/s|ft/s|sp=us}}. Even if Dragon were to lose one of its main parachutes, the two remaining chutes would still permit a safe landing. The Dragon capsule is expected to land in the Pacific Ocean, about {{convert|450|km|mi|abbr=on}} off the coast of southern California. SpaceX uses a 100-foot boat equipped with an A-frame and an articulating crane, a 90-foot crew boat for telemetry operations, and two 24-foot rigid-hull inflatable boats to perform recovery operations. On board are approximately a dozen SpaceX engineers and technicians as well as a four-person dive team. Once the Dragon capsule splashed down, the recovery team secured the vehicle and then placed it on deck for the journey back to shore.{{Failed verification|date=November 2012}}<!-- a source from before the flight does not confirm that the planned event became a past-tense historical fact; needs a better source, or the prose needs to speak to the mission plan as outlined in the presskit --><ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\nSpaceX technicians opened the side hatch of the vehicle and retrieved the time-critical items. The critical cargo items were placed on a fast-boat for the 450-Kilometer trip back to California for eventual return to NASA that then took care of the precious science cargo and handle post-flight analysis of the samples.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spaceflight101.com/dragon-crs-1-mission-updates.html |title=Dragon CRS-1 Mission Updates |publisher=SPACEFLIGHT101 |accessdate=8 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212070813/http://www.spaceflight101.com/dragon-crs-1-mission-updates.html |archivedate=12 February 2013  }}</ref> The rest of the cargo was unloaded once the Dragon capsule reached SpaceX's test facility in McGregor, Texas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121028splashdown/ |title=Dragon Mission Report &#124; Return of the Dragon: Commercial craft back home |publisher=Spaceflight Now |date= |accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Payload ==\n[[File:CRS SpX-1 Dragon int.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Dragon spacecraft being integrated onto Falcon 9 on 30 September 2012]]\n\n=== Primary payload ===\nWhen launched the CRS-1 Dragon was filled with about {{convert|1995|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of cargo, {{convert|882|lb|kg|abbr=on}} without packaging.<ref name=Presskit/> Included was {{convert|260|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of crew supplies, {{convert|390|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of critical materials to support the 166 experiments on board the station and 66 new experiments, as well as {{convert|232|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of hardware for the station as well as other miscellaneous items.<ref name=Presskit/>\n\nThe Dragon returned {{convert|1995|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of cargo, {{convert|1673|lb|kg|abbr=on}} without packaging.<ref name=Presskit/> Included was {{convert|163|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of crew supplies, {{convert|866|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of scientific experiments and experiment hardware, {{convert|518|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of space station hardware, {{convert|68|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of [[spacesuit]] equipment and {{convert|55|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of miscellaneous items.<ref name=Presskit/>\n\n=== Secondary payload ===\nFor some months prior to the launch, a {{convert|150|kg|lb|abbr=on}} prototype second-generation [[Orbcomm (satellite)|Orbcomm satellite]] was planned to be launched as a [[secondary payload]] from Falcon 9's second stage.<ref name=\"Orbcomm 25 May 2012\" /><ref name=\"Hartman 23 July 2012\" />\n\nAlthough the secondary payload made it to the Dragon insertion orbit, an engine anomaly on one of the nine engines on the Falcon 9 first stage during the ascent resulted in automatic engine shutdown and a longer first-stage burn on the remaining eight engines to complete orbital insertion while subsequently increasing use of propellant over the nominal mission.\n\nThe primary payload contractor, NASA, requires a greater-than-99% estimated probability that the stage of any secondary payload on a similar orbital inclination to the [[International Space Station]] will reach their orbital altitude goal above the station. Due to the engine failure, the Falcon 9 used more [[Rocket propellant|propellant]] than intended, reducing the success probability estimate to approximately 95%. Because of this, the second stage did not attempt a second burn, and Orbcomm-G2 was left in an unusable orbit<ref name=sfn20121011>{{cite web |url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121011orbcomm/ |title=Orbcomm craft falls to Earth, company claims total loss |publisher=Spaceflight Now |first=Stephen |last=Clark |accessdate=11 October 2012 |date=11 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-spacex-statement-review-of-1st-stage-engine-failure.html |title=SpaceX CRS-1: SpaceX statement - review of 1st stage engine failure |work=NewSpace Watch |first=Clark |last=Lindsey |date=10 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130129221059/http://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-spacex-statement-review-of-1st-stage-engine-failure.html |archivedate=29 January 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and burned up in Earth's atmosphere within 4 days after the launch.<ref name=sn20121011>{{cite news |last=de Selding |first=Peter B. |title=Orbcomm Craft Launched by Falcon 9 Falls out of Orbit |url=http://www.spacenews.com/article/orbcomm-craft-launched-by-falcon-9-falls-out-of-orbit |accessdate=9 March 2014 |newspaper=Space News |date=11 October 2012 |quote=Orbcomm requested that SpaceX carry one of their small satellites (weighing a few hundred pounds, vs. Dragon at over 12,000 pounds)... The higher the orbit, the more test data [Orbcomm] can gather, so they requested that we attempt to restart and raise altitude. NASA agreed to allow that, but only on condition that there be substantial propellant reserves, since the orbit would be close to the space station.  It is important to appreciate that Orbcomm understood from the beginning that the orbit-raising maneuver was tentative. They accepted that there was a high risk of their satellite remaining at the Dragon insertion orbit. SpaceX would not have agreed to fly their satellite otherwise, since this was not part of the core mission and there was a known, material risk of no altitude raise.}}</ref><ref name=\"orbcomm total loss\">[http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121011orbcomm/ Orbcomm craft falls to Earth, company claims total loss]</ref>\n\nBoth SpaceX and Orbcomm were aware, prior to the mission, of the high risk that the secondary payload satellite could remain at the lower altitude of the Dragon insertion orbit, and that was a risk that Orbcomm agreed to take given the dramatically lower cost of launch for a secondary payload.<ref name=sn20121011/>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Launch attempts ==\n\n{{LaunchAttempt\n|df=yes| date1 = 2012-10-08 00:34:07 UTC\n| result1 = Partial Success: success for primary payload, failure for secondary payload\n| reason1 = \n| decision_date1 = \n| decision_clock1= \n| weathergo1 = 80<ref name=\"NASA EH\">{{cite video |title=NASA Education Hour |publisher=NASA TV |date=8 October 2012 |location=Television}}</ref><ref name=\"NASA Station Archive\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/living/launch/crs_rss_feed_collection_archive_1.html |title='Everything is Looking Real Good for Launch' |publisher=NASA |date=7 October 2012 |accessdate=7 October 2012}}</ref>\n| notes1 = At 79 seconds into the launch, Engine 1 lost pressure and was commanded by the rocket to shut down.<ref name=\"SpaceX CRS-1 Mission Update\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spacex.com/press/2012/12/19/spacex-crs-1-mission-update|title=SPACEX CRS-1 MISSION UPDATE |accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> Due to the engine failure on the first stage, safety protocols for rendezvous with the ISS prevented the secondary-payload Orbcomm Satellite from being placed in the correct orbit.<ref name=\"Orbcomm OG2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.orbcomm.com/pdf/files/ORBCOMM_Launches_Prototype_OG2_Satellite_FINAL.pdf |title=ORBCOMM LAUNCHES PROTOTYPE OG2 SATELLITE |accessdate=9 October 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021004407/http://www.orbcomm.com/Collateral/Documents/English-US/ORBCOMM%20Launches%20Prototype%20OG2%20Satellite%20FINAL.pdf |archive-date=21 October 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n== Falcon 9 engine anomaly ==\n[[File:SpaceX CRS-1 Launch.ogv|thumb|right|Video of the launch of SpaceX CRS-1 Falcon 9]]\n\nDuring the ascent, 79 seconds<ref name=innerspace20121009 /> after launch, an engine anomaly occurred with one of the nine engines on the Falcon 9 first stage.  SpaceX has emphasized for several years that the Falcon 9 first stage is designed for \"engine out\" capability, with the capability to shut down one or more malfunctioning engines and still make a successful ascent.<ref name=\"sxf9o20100508\">{{cite news |url=http://www.spacex.com/falcon9.php |title=Falcon 9 Overview |date=8 May 2010 |publisher=SpaceX}}</ref>  In the event, the SpaceX CRS-1's first stage shut down engine no.&nbsp;1, and as a result continued the first-stage burn on the remaining eight engines longer than usual at a somewhat reduced thrust to insert the Dragon spacecraft into the proper orbit.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-post-conference-press-conference.html |title=SpaceX CRS-1: Post conference press conference |work=NewSpace Watch |first=Clark |last=Lindsey |date=8 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121217163116/https://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-post-conference-press-conference.html |archivedate=17 December 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Although unintended, this was the first inflight demonstration of Falcon 9's \"engine out\" design,<ref name=tsr20121008/><ref name=lat20121008>{{cite news |last=Hennigan |first=WJ |title=SpaceX rocket engine shuts down during launch to station |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/money/la-fi-mo-spacex-engine-problem-20121008,0,67936.story |accessdate=8 October 2012 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=8 October 2012}}</ref> and \"provides a clear demonstration of the engine out capability.\"<ref name=aw20121126>{{cite news |last=Svitak |first=Amy |title=Falcon 9 RUD? |url=http://www.aviationweek.com/Blogs.aspx?plckBlogId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385&plckPostId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385Post:c973f72f-55d3-4374-b722-df31a8d333e6 |accessdate=21 March 2014 |newspaper=Aviation Week |date=26 November 2012}}</ref><ref name=innerspace20121009>{{cite news |last=Money |first=Stewart |title=Falcon 9 Loses an Engine (and Fairing), Demonstrates Resiliance |url=http://innerspace.net/2012/10/09/falcon-9-loses-an-engine-and-fairing-demonstrates-resiliance/ |accessdate=10 October 2012 |newspaper=Innerspace |date=9 October 2012 |quote=''provides a clear demonstration of the engine out capability.''}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the anomaly, NASA and SpaceX jointly formed the CRS-1 Post-Flight Investigation Board.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-review-board-formed-to-investigate-engine-failure.html |title=SpaceX CRS-1: Review board formed to investigate engine failure |work=NewSpace Watch |first=Clark |last=Lindsey |date=12 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130129203156/http://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-review-board-formed-to-investigate-engine-failure.html |archivedate=29 January 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Preliminary information from the post-flight review board indicates that the Engine no. 1 fuel dome, above the nozzle, ruptured but did not explode.  The burning fuel that exited before the engine was shut down caused the fairing rupture, as seen in the flight video recordings.<ref name=nsf20121019>{{cite news |last=Bergin |first=Chris |title=Dragon enjoying ISS stay, despite minor issues \u2013 Falcon 9 investigation begins |url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2012/10/dragon-iss-stay-minor-issues-falcon-9-investigation/ |accessdate=21 October 2012 |newspaper=NASAspaceflight.com |date=19 October 2012 |quote=''The first stage issue related to Engine 1, one of nine Merlin 1Cs, after \u2013 it is understood \u2013 the fuel dome above the nozzle ruptured. The engine did not explode, but did cause the fairing that protects the engine from aerodynamic loads to rupture and fall away from the vehicle due to the engine pressure release.''}}</ref> Subsequent investigations revealed in a Congressional hearing pinpointed the issue as a result of an undetected material flaw in the engine chamber jacket, likely introduced during engine production. During flight, the data suggests this material flaw ultimately developed into a breach in the main combustion chamber. This breach released a jet of hot gas and fuel in the direction of the main fuel line causing a secondary leak and ultimately a rapid drop in engine pressure. As a result, the flight computer commanded shutdown of engine 1 and Falcon 9 continued on its path to ensure Dragon's entry into orbit for subsequent rendezvous and berthing with the ISS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviationweek.com/blog/spacex-engine-anomaly-overview |title=SpaceX: Engine Anomaly Overview |publisher=Aviationweek.com |date= |accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* [[List of Falcon 9 launches]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist |colwidth=30em |refs=\n\n<ref name=HARTMAN>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/672214main_1-Hartman_July12_NAC_Final_508.pdf |title=International Space Station Program Status |last=Hartman |first=Dan |date=23 July 2012 |publisher=NASA |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Presskit\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/694166main_SpaceXCRS-1PressKit.pdf |title=SpX CRS-1 Mission Press Kit |date=4 October 2012 |publisher=NASA, SpaceX, 45th Space Wing |accessdate=6 October 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SpaceX Launch Manifest\">\n{{cite web |title=SpaceX Launch Manifest |publisher=SpaceX |url=http://www.spacex.com/launch_manifest.php |accessdate=31 May 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NASA Launch Schedule\">\n{{cite web |title=NASA's Consolidated Launch Schedule |publisher=NASA |url=http://www.nasa.gov/missions/highlights/schedule.html |accessdate=21 June 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NASAsept20\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/main/spacex-crs1-target.html |title=SpaceX, NASA Target Oct. 7 Launch For Resupply Mission To Space Station |date=20 September 2012 |publisher=NASA |accessdate=26 September 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Clark 18 May 2012\">\n{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=18 May 2012 |title=SpaceX's historic commercial mission is 'just a test flight' |publisher=SpaceFlightNow |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/003/120518commercial/ |accessdate=25 August 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=ClarkOct28>{{cite web |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121028splashdown/#.UI_fCIa_PKg |title=Return of the Dragon: Commercial craft back home |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=28 October 2012 |publisher=SpaceFlightNow |accessdate=30 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Clark 24 August 2012\">\n{{cite web |title=NASA ready for operational cargo flights by SpaceX |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=24 August 2012 |publisher=SpaceFlightNow |url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n1208/24cots/ |accessdate=25 August 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=SPACENOW10>{{cite web |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121010arrival/ |title=Dragon arrives at station with commercial delivery |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=10 October 2012 |publisher=SpaceFlightNow |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Orbcomm 25 May 2012\">\n{{cite press |title=Orbcomm Eagerly Awaits Launch of New Satellite on Next Falcon 9 |date=25 May 2012 |publisher=Space News |url=http://www.spacenews.com/satellite_telecom/120525-spacex-success-welcome-orbcomm.html |accessdate=28 May 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hartman 23 July 2012\">\n{{cite web |last=Hartman |first=Dan |date=23 July 2012 |title=International Space Station Program Status |publisher=NASA |url=http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/672214main_1-Hartman_July12_NAC_Final_508.pdf |accessdate=28 August 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sept29\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2012/09/falcon-9-hot-fires-engines-iss-prepares-dragons-arrival/ |title=Falcon 9 hot fires its engines as the ISS prepares for Dragon's arrival |last=Bergin |first=Chris |date=29 September 2012 |publisher=NASASpaceFlight (not associated with NASA) |accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AugustChris\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2012/08/spacex-conduct-successful-wdr-falcon-9/ |title=SpaceX conduct successful WDR on their latest Falcon 9 |last=Bergin |first=Chris |date=31 August 2012 |publisher=NASASpaceFlight (not associated with NASA) |accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|SpaceX CRS-1}}\n*[http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/living/launch/index.html SpaceX CRS-1 NASA page]\n*[http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/694166main_SpaceXCRS-1PressKit.pdf SpaceX CRS-1 Mission Press Kit (4 October 2012)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5I7loLnDYyU Video of Static Fire test - YouTube (spacexchannel)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tRTYh71D9P0 Video of Launch - YouTube (spacexchannel)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lg5vd_Gs0G4 Video of Approach, Grappling and Berthing of Dragon - YouTube (ReelNASA)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NAXBdt5gS_c Video of Hatch Opening - YouTube (NASATelevision)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W_bF6ZciBxQ Video of Dragon Splashdown - YouTube (spacexchannel)]\n\n{{Dragon spaceflights}}\n{{Falcon rocket launches}}\n{{Unmanned ISS resupply flights}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:CRS 001}}\n[[Category:SpaceX Dragon]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2012]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 2012]]\n[[Category:SpaceX payloads contracted by NASA]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = SpaceX CRS-1\n| image                 = SpaceX CRS-1 approaches ISS-cropped.jpg\n| image_caption         = The Dragon CRS-1 is seen approaching the ISS.\n| insignia              = SpaceX CRS-1 Patch.png\n| insignia_caption      = NASA SpX-1 mission patch\n\n| mission_type          = [[International Space Station|ISS]] resupply\n| operator              = [[NASA]]\n| COSPAR_ID             = 2012-054A\n| SATCAT                = 38846\n| mission_duration      = {{time interval|8 October 2012 00:34:07|28 October 2012 19:22|show=dhm|sep=,}}\n\n| spacecraft            = Dragon C103\n| spacecraft_type       = [[SpaceX Dragon#Dragon CRS|Dragon CRS]]\n| manufacturer          = [[SpaceX]]\n| dry_mass              = \n| launch_mass           = \n\n| launch_date           = 8 October 2012<br/>00:34:07 UTC <ref name=\"NASA EH\"/><ref name=NASAsept20/>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Falcon 9]] v1.0\n| launch_site           = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 40|SLC-40]] <ref name=\"SpaceX Launch Manifest\"/><ref name=\"NASA Launch Schedule\"/>\n| launch_contractor     = [[SpaceX]]\n| disposal_type         = Recovered\n| landing_date          = {{end-date|28 October 2012, 19:22|timezone=yes}} UTC <ref name=ClarkOct28/>\n| landing_site          = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n\n| orbit_epoch           = 8 October 2012\n| orbit_reference       = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime          = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis       = \n| orbit_apoapsis        = \n| orbit_inclination     = 51.6\u00b0\n| orbit_period          = \n| apsis                 = gee\n\n| docking               = \n {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target     = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n   | docking_type       = berth\n   | docking_port       = [[Harmony (ISS module)|Harmony]]\n   | capture_date       = 10 October 2012, 10:56 UTC\n   | docking_date       = 10 October 2012, 13:03 UTC <ref name=SPACENOW10/>\n   | undocking_date     = 28 October 2012, 11:19 UTC <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aviationweek.com/Blogs.aspx?plckBlogId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385&plckPostId=Blog%3A04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385Post%3A4cbd3925-a48e-4c00-a26e-1e90c4466f96|title=SpaceX Dragon CRS-1 Capsule Departs Space Station|last=Carreau|first=Mark|date=28 October 2012|publisher=Aviation Week|accessdate=30 October 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006200230/http://www.aviationweek.com/Blogs.aspx?plckBlogId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385|archivedate=6 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n   | release_date       = 28 October 2012, 13:29 UTC\n   | time_docked        = 17 days 22 hours 16 minutes\n }}\n\n| cargo_mass            = 400 kg\n| cargo_mass_press      = 400 kg\n| cargo_mass_unpress    = \n| cargo_mass_fuel       = \n| cargo_mass_gas        = \n| cargo_mass_water      = \n\n| programme             = [[Commercial Resupply Services]]\n| previous_mission      = [[Dragon C2+]]\n| next_mission          = [[SpaceX CRS-2]]\n}}\n\n'''SpaceX CRS-1''', also known as '''SpX-1''',<ref name=HARTMAN/> was the third flight for [[SpaceX|Space Exploration Technologies Corporation's]] (SpaceX) uncrewed [[SpaceX Dragon|Dragon]] [[Comparison of space station cargo vehicles|cargo spacecraft]], the fourth overall flight for the company's two-stage [[Falcon 9]] launch vehicle, and the first SpaceX operational mission under their [[Commercial Resupply Services]] contract with [[NASA]]. The launch occurred on 8 October 2012 at 00:34:07 UTC.<ref name=\"NASA EH\"/><ref name=NASAsept20/><ref name=wsj20120707-8:38pm>{{Cite news|last=Pasztor|first=Andy|title=SpaceX Launches Cargo Flight to Space Station|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443482404578043100196815928|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Spaceflight Now\"/>\n\n== History ==\nIn May 2012, it was reported that the Falcon 9 had been transported to [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]].<ref name=\"Clark 18 May 2012\"/> The Dragon CRS-1 arrived on 14 August 2012.<ref name=\"Clark 24 August 2012\"/> On 31 August 2012, a [[wet dress rehearsal]] (WDR) was completed for the Falcon 9, and on 29 September a static fire test was completed; both of these tests were completed without the Dragon capsule attached to the launch vehicle stack.<ref name=AugustChris/><ref name=Sept29/> The mission passed its Launch Readiness Review (LRR) on 5 October 2012.<ref name=\"Spaceflight Now\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121005preview/|title=Commercial resupply of space station blasts off Sunday|publisher=SpaceFlightNow|date=5 October 2012|accessdate=6 October 2012|last=Clark |first=Stephen}}</ref>\n\nThe launch occurred on 8 October 2012 at 00:34:07 UTC and successfully placed the Dragon spacecraft into the proper orbit for arriving at the International Space Station with cargo resupply several days later. During the launch, one of the nine engines suffered a sudden loss of pressure 79 seconds into the flight, and an immediate early shutdown of that engine occurred; debris could be seen in the telescopic video of the night launch. The remaining eight engines fired for a longer period of time and the flight control software adjusted the trajectory to insert Dragon into a near-flawless [[low-Earth orbit|orbit]].<ref name=tsr20121008>{{cite news|last=Foust|first=Jeff|title=Commercial spaceflight gets down to business|url=http://thespacereview.com/article/2168/1|accessdate=10 October 2012|newspaper=The Space Review |date=8 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Mission timeline ==\n\n=== Flight day 1, launch (8 October) ===\n[[File:SpaceX CRS-1 launch cropped.jpg|thumb|left|The SpaceX CRS-1 Falcon 9 launches on 8 October 2012.]]\n\nThe mission plan, as published by NASA before the mission, called for the Falcon 9 to reach [[supersonic speed]] at 70 seconds after liftoff, and pass through the area of maximum aerodynamic pressure, \"[[max Q]]\" \u2014 the point when mechanical stress on the rocket peaks due to a combination of the rocket's velocity and resistance created by the Earth's atmosphere \u2014 10 seconds later. The plan called for two of the first-stage engines to shut down to reduce the rocket's acceleration at approximately 2 minutes 30 seconds into the flight when the Falcon 9 would nominally be {{convert|90|km|mi}} high and traveling at 10 times the speed of sound. The remaining engines were planned to cut off shortly after\u2014an event known as main-engine cutoff (MECO). Five seconds after MECO, the first and second stages separate. Seven seconds later, the second stage's single Merlin vacuum engine was projected to ignite to begin a 6-minute, 14-second burn to put Dragon into [[low-Earth orbit]]. Forty seconds after second-stage ignition, Dragon's protective nose cone, which covers Dragon's berthing mechanism, was planned to be jettisoned. At the 9-minute, 14-second mark after launch, the second-stage engine was scheduled to cut off (SECO). Thirty-five seconds later, Dragon was planned to separate from Falcon 9's second stage and reach its preliminary orbit. The dragon would, per plan, then deploy its solar arrays and open its guidance and navigation control (GNC) bay door which holds the sensors necessary for rendezvous and Dragon's [[Power Data Grapple Fixture|grapple fixture]].<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\n=== Flight day 2 (9 October) ===\nThe mission plan called for the Dragon spacecraft to perform a coelliptic burn that would place it in a circular [[coelliptic orbit]].<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\n=== Flight day 3 (10 October) ===\nAs Dragon chased the [[International Space Station]], the spacecraft established UHF communication using its COTS Ultra-high-frequency Communication Unit (CUCU). Also, using the crew command panel (CCP) onboard the station, the expedition crew monitored the approach. This ability for the crew to send commands to Dragon is important during the rendezvous and departure phases of the mission.<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\nDuring the final approach to the station, a go/no-go was performed by [[Christopher C. Kraft Jr. Mission Control Center#FCR 1 (2006-present)|Mission Control Houston]] and the SpaceX team in Hawthorne to allow Dragon to perform another engine burn that brought it {{convert|250|m|ft}} from the station. At this distance, Dragon began using its close-range guidance systems, composed of [[LIDAR]] and thermal imagers. These systems confirmed that Dragon's position and velocity are accurate by comparing the LIDAR image that Dragon receives against Dragon's thermal imagers. The Dragon flight control team in Hawthorne, with assistance from the NASA flight control team at the Johnson Space Center's International Space Station Flight Control Room, commanded the spacecraft to approach the station from its hold position. After another go/no-go was performed by the Houston and Hawthorne teams, Dragon was permitted to enter the Keep-Out Sphere (KOS), an imaginary sphere drawn {{convert|200|m|ft}} around the station that reduces the risk of collision. Dragon proceeded to a position {{convert|30|m|ft}} from the station and was automatically held. Another go/no-go was completed. Then Dragon proceeded to the {{convert|10|m|ft}} position \u2014 the capture point. A final go/no-go was performed, and the Mission Control Houston team notified the crew they were going for the capture of Dragon.<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\nAt that point, Expedition 33 crewmember [[Akihiko Hoshide]] of the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency used the station's {{convert|17.6|m|ft}} robotic arm, known as [[Mobile Servicing System#Canadarm2 |Canadarm2]], reached for and grappled the Dragon spacecraft at 10:56 UTC.<ref name=SPACENOW10/> Hoshide, with the help of Expedition 33 Commander [[Sunita Williams]] of NASA, guided Dragon to the Earth-facing side of the station's [[Harmony module]]. Williams and Hoshide swapped places and Williams gently berthed Dragon to Harmony's [[Common Berthing Mechanism]] at 13:03 UTC.<ref name=SPACENOW10/>\n\nThe opening of the hatch between Dragon and the Harmony module, which was originally not scheduled to occur until 11 October, was moved up and occurred at 17:40 UTC.<ref name=SPACENOW10/>\n\n=== Remainder of mission (11 to 28 October) ===\n[[File:SpX CRS-1 berthed - cropped.jpg|thumb|right|Dragon as seen from [[Cupola (ISS module)|Cupola]] on 14 October 2012]]\nOver a period of two and a half weeks, the ISS crew unloaded Dragon's payload and reloaded it with cargo for return to Earth.<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>{{Failed verification|date=November 2012}}<!-- a source from before the flight does not confirm that the planned event became a past-tense historical fact; needs a better source, or the prose needs to speak to the mission plan as outlined in the presskit -->\n\nAfter its mission at the orbital laboratory was completed, newly arrived Expedition 33 Flight Engineer [[Kevin A. Ford|Kevin Ford]] used the Canadarm2 robotic arm to detach Dragon from Harmony, maneuver it out to the 15-meter (50-foot) release point, and release the vehicle. Dragon then performed a series of three burns to place it on a trajectory away from the station. Approximately six hours after Dragon departed the station, it conducted a deorbit burn, which lasted up to 10 minutes. Dragon's trunk, which contains its solar arrays, was then jettisoned.<ref name=\"Presskit\"/>{{Failed verification|date=November 2012}}<!-- a source from before the flight does not confirm that the planned event became a past-tense historical fact; needs a better source, or the prose needs to speak to the mission plan as outlined in the presskit -->\n[[File:SpX-1 Dragon at port.1.jpg|thumb|left|The SpX-1 capsule seen back at port on 30 October 2012]]\nThe landing was controlled by automatic firing of its [[Draco (rocket engine family)#Draco|Draco]] thrusters during [[Atmospheric entry|reentry]].{{Failed verification|date=November 2012}}<!-- a source from before the flight does not confirm that the planned event became a past-tense historical fact; needs a better source, or the prose needs to speak to the mission plan as outlined in the presskit --> In a carefully timed sequence of events, dual [[drogue parachute]]s deploy at an altitude of {{convert|13700|m|ft|abbr=on}} to stabilize and slow the spacecraft. Full deployment of the drogues triggers the release of the three main parachutes, each 35 meters (116 feet) in diameter, at about {{convert|3000|m|ft|abbr=on}}. While the drogues detach from the spacecraft, the main parachutes further slow the spacecraft's descent to approximately {{convert|4.8|to|5.4|m/s|ft/s|sp=us}}. Even if Dragon were to lose one of its main parachutes, the two remaining chutes would still permit a safe landing. The Dragon capsule is expected to land in the Pacific Ocean, about {{convert|450|km|mi|abbr=on}} off the coast of southern California. SpaceX uses a 100-foot boat equipped with an A-frame and an articulating crane, a 90-foot crew boat for telemetry operations, and two 24-foot rigid-hull inflatable boats to perform recovery operations. On board are approximately a dozen SpaceX engineers and technicians as well as a four-person dive team. Once the Dragon capsule splashed down, the recovery team secured the vehicle and then placed it on deck for the journey back to shore.{{Failed verification|date=November 2012}}<!-- a source from before the flight does not confirm that the planned event became a past-tense historical fact; needs a better source, or the prose needs to speak to the mission plan as outlined in the presskit --><ref name=\"Presskit\"/>\n\nSpaceX technicians opened the side hatch of the vehicle and retrieved the time-critical items. The critical cargo items were placed on a fast-boat for the 450-Kilometer trip back to California for eventual return to NASA that then took care of the precious science cargo and handle post-flight analysis of the samples.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spaceflight101.com/dragon-crs-1-mission-updates.html |title=Dragon CRS-1 Mission Updates |publisher=SPACEFLIGHT101 |accessdate=8 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212070813/http://www.spaceflight101.com/dragon-crs-1-mission-updates.html |archivedate=12 February 2013  }}</ref> The rest of the cargo was unloaded once the Dragon capsule reached SpaceX's test facility in McGregor, Texas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121028splashdown/ |title=Dragon Mission Report &#124; Return of the Dragon: Commercial craft back home |publisher=Spaceflight Now |date= |accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Payload ==\n[[File:CRS SpX-1 Dragon int.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Dragon spacecraft being integrated onto Falcon 9 on 30 September 2012]]\n\n=== Primary payload ===\nWhen launched the CRS-1 Dragon was filled with about {{convert|1995|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of cargo, {{convert|882|lb|kg|abbr=on}} without packaging.<ref name=Presskit/> Included was {{convert|260|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of crew supplies, {{convert|390|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of critical materials to support the 166 experiments on board the station and 66 new experiments, as well as {{convert|232|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of hardware for the station as well as other miscellaneous items.<ref name=Presskit/>\n\nThe Dragon returned {{convert|1995|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of cargo, {{convert|1673|lb|kg|abbr=on}} without packaging.<ref name=Presskit/> Included was {{convert|163|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of crew supplies, {{convert|866|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of scientific experiments and experiment hardware, {{convert|518|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of space station hardware, {{convert|68|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of [[spacesuit]] equipment and {{convert|55|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of miscellaneous items.<ref name=Presskit/>\n\n=== Secondary payload ===\nFor some months prior to the launch, a {{convert|150|kg|lb|abbr=on}} prototype second-generation [[Orbcomm (satellite)|Orbcomm satellite]] was planned to be launched as a [[secondary payload]] from Falcon 9's second stage.<ref name=\"Orbcomm 25 May 2012\" /><ref name=\"Hartman 23 July 2012\" />\n\nAlthough the secondary payload made it to the Dragon insertion orbit, an engine anomaly on one of the nine engines on the Falcon 9 first stage during the ascent resulted in automatic engine shutdown and a longer first-stage burn on the remaining eight engines to complete orbital insertion while subsequently increasing use of propellant over the nominal mission.\n\nThe primary payload contractor, NASA, requires a greater-than-99% estimated probability that the stage of any secondary payload on a similar orbital inclination to the [[International Space Station]] will reach their orbital altitude goal above the station. Due to the engine failure, the Falcon 9 used more [[Rocket propellant|propellant]] than intended, reducing the success probability estimate to approximately 95%. Because of this, the second stage did not attempt a second burn, and Orbcomm-G2 was left in an unusable orbit<ref name=sfn20121011>{{cite web |url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121011orbcomm/ |title=Orbcomm craft falls to Earth, company claims total loss |publisher=Spaceflight Now |first=Stephen |last=Clark |accessdate=11 October 2012 |date=11 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-spacex-statement-review-of-1st-stage-engine-failure.html |title=SpaceX CRS-1: SpaceX statement - review of 1st stage engine failure |work=NewSpace Watch |first=Clark |last=Lindsey |date=10 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130129221059/http://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-spacex-statement-review-of-1st-stage-engine-failure.html |archivedate=29 January 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and burned up in Earth's atmosphere within 4 days after the launch.<ref name=sn20121011>{{cite news |last=de Selding |first=Peter B. |title=Orbcomm Craft Launched by Falcon 9 Falls out of Orbit |url=http://www.spacenews.com/article/orbcomm-craft-launched-by-falcon-9-falls-out-of-orbit |accessdate=9 March 2014 |newspaper=Space News |date=11 October 2012 |quote=Orbcomm requested that SpaceX carry one of their small satellites (weighing a few hundred pounds, vs. Dragon at over 12,000 pounds)... The higher the orbit, the more test data [Orbcomm] can gather, so they requested that we attempt to restart and raise altitude. NASA agreed to allow that, but only on condition that there be substantial propellant reserves, since the orbit would be close to the space station.  It is important to appreciate that Orbcomm understood from the beginning that the orbit-raising maneuver was tentative. They accepted that there was a high risk of their satellite remaining at the Dragon insertion orbit. SpaceX would not have agreed to fly their satellite otherwise, since this was not part of the core mission and there was a known, material risk of no altitude raise.}}</ref><ref name=\"orbcomm total loss\">[http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121011orbcomm/ Orbcomm craft falls to Earth, company claims total loss]</ref>\n\nBoth SpaceX and Orbcomm were aware, prior to the mission, of the high risk that the secondary payload satellite could remain at the lower altitude of the Dragon insertion orbit, and that was a risk that Orbcomm agreed to take given the dramatically lower cost of launch for a secondary payload.<ref name=sn20121011/>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Launch attempts ==\n\n{{LaunchAttempt\n|df=yes| date1 = 2012-10-08 00:34:07 UTC\n| result1 = Partial Success: success for primary payload, failure for secondary payload\n| reason1 = \n| decision_date1 = \n| decision_clock1= \n| weathergo1 = 80<ref name=\"NASA EH\">{{cite video |title=NASA Education Hour |publisher=NASA TV |date=8 October 2012 |location=Television}}</ref><ref name=\"NASA Station Archive\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/living/launch/crs_rss_feed_collection_archive_1.html |title='Everything is Looking Real Good for Launch' |publisher=NASA |date=7 October 2012 |accessdate=7 October 2012}}</ref>\n| notes1 = At 79 seconds into the launch, Engine 1 lost pressure and was commanded by the rocket to shut down.<ref name=\"SpaceX CRS-1 Mission Update\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spacex.com/press/2012/12/19/spacex-crs-1-mission-update|title=SPACEX CRS-1 MISSION UPDATE |accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> Due to the engine failure on the first stage, safety protocols for rendezvous with the ISS prevented the secondary-payload Orbcomm Satellite from being placed in the correct orbit.<ref name=\"Orbcomm OG2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.orbcomm.com/pdf/files/ORBCOMM_Launches_Prototype_OG2_Satellite_FINAL.pdf |title=ORBCOMM LAUNCHES PROTOTYPE OG2 SATELLITE |accessdate=9 October 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021004407/http://www.orbcomm.com/Collateral/Documents/English-US/ORBCOMM%20Launches%20Prototype%20OG2%20Satellite%20FINAL.pdf |archive-date=21 October 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n== Falcon 9 engine anomaly ==\n[[File:SpaceX CRS-1 Launch.ogv|thumb|right|Video of the launch of SpaceX CRS-1 Falcon 9]]\n\nDuring the ascent, 79 seconds<ref name=innerspace20121009 /> after launch, an engine anomaly occurred with one of the nine engines on the Falcon 9 first stage.  SpaceX has emphasized for several years that the Falcon 9 first stage is designed for \"engine out\" capability, with the capability to shut down one or more malfunctioning engines and still make a successful ascent.<ref name=\"sxf9o20100508\">{{cite news |url=http://www.spacex.com/falcon9.php |title=Falcon 9 Overview |date=8 May 2010 |publisher=SpaceX}}</ref>  In the event, the SpaceX CRS-1's first stage shut down engine no.&nbsp;1, and as a result continued the first-stage burn on the remaining eight engines longer than usual at a somewhat reduced thrust to insert the Dragon spacecraft into the proper orbit.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-post-conference-press-conference.html |title=SpaceX CRS-1: Post conference press conference |work=NewSpace Watch |first=Clark |last=Lindsey |date=8 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121217163116/https://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-post-conference-press-conference.html |archivedate=17 December 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Although unintended, this was the first inflight demonstration of Falcon 9's \"engine out\" design,<ref name=tsr20121008/><ref name=lat20121008>{{cite news |last=Hennigan |first=WJ |title=SpaceX rocket engine shuts down during launch to station |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/money/la-fi-mo-spacex-engine-problem-20121008,0,67936.story |accessdate=8 October 2012 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=8 October 2012}}</ref> and \"provides a clear demonstration of the engine out capability.\"<ref name=aw20121126>{{cite news |last=Svitak |first=Amy |title=Falcon 9 RUD? |url=http://www.aviationweek.com/Blogs.aspx?plckBlogId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385&plckPostId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385Post:c973f72f-55d3-4374-b722-df31a8d333e6 |accessdate=21 March 2014 |newspaper=Aviation Week |date=26 November 2012}}</ref><ref name=innerspace20121009>{{cite news |last=Money |first=Stewart |title=Falcon 9 Loses an Engine (and Fairing), Demonstrates Resiliance |url=http://innerspace.net/2012/10/09/falcon-9-loses-an-engine-and-fairing-demonstrates-resiliance/ |accessdate=10 October 2012 |newspaper=Innerspace |date=9 October 2012 |quote=''provides a clear demonstration of the engine out capability.''}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the anomaly, NASA and SpaceX jointly formed the CRS-1 Post-Flight Investigation Board.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-review-board-formed-to-investigate-engine-failure.html |title=SpaceX CRS-1: Review board formed to investigate engine failure |work=NewSpace Watch |first=Clark |last=Lindsey |date=12 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130129203156/http://www.newspacewatch.com/articles/spacex-crs-1-review-board-formed-to-investigate-engine-failure.html |archivedate=29 January 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Preliminary information from the post-flight review board indicates that the Engine no. 1 fuel dome, above the nozzle, ruptured but did not explode.  The burning fuel that exited before the engine was shut down caused the fairing rupture, as seen in the flight video recordings.<ref name=nsf20121019>{{cite news |last=Bergin |first=Chris |title=Dragon enjoying ISS stay, despite minor issues \u2013 Falcon 9 investigation begins |url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2012/10/dragon-iss-stay-minor-issues-falcon-9-investigation/ |accessdate=21 October 2012 |newspaper=NASAspaceflight.com |date=19 October 2012 |quote=''The first stage issue related to Engine 1, one of nine Merlin 1Cs, after \u2013 it is understood \u2013 the fuel dome above the nozzle ruptured. The engine did not explode, but did cause the fairing that protects the engine from aerodynamic loads to rupture and fall away from the vehicle due to the engine pressure release.''}}</ref> Subsequent investigations revealed in a Congressional hearing pinpointed the issue as a result of an undetected material flaw in the engine chamber jacket, likely introduced during engine production. During flight, the data suggests this material flaw ultimately developed into a breach in the main combustion chamber. This breach released a jet of hot gas and fuel in the direction of the main fuel line causing a secondary leak and ultimately a rapid drop in engine pressure. As a result, the flight computer commanded shutdown of engine 1 and Falcon 9 continued on its path to ensure Dragon's entry into orbit for subsequent rendezvous and berthing with the ISS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviationweek.com/blog/spacex-engine-anomaly-overview |title=SpaceX: Engine Anomaly Overview |publisher=Aviationweek.com |date= |accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* [[List of Falcon 9 launches]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist |colwidth=30em |refs=\n\n<ref name=HARTMAN>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/672214main_1-Hartman_July12_NAC_Final_508.pdf |title=International Space Station Program Status |last=Hartman |first=Dan |date=23 July 2012 |publisher=NASA |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Presskit\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/694166main_SpaceXCRS-1PressKit.pdf |title=SpX CRS-1 Mission Press Kit |date=4 October 2012 |publisher=NASA, SpaceX, 45th Space Wing |accessdate=6 October 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SpaceX Launch Manifest\">\n{{cite web |title=SpaceX Launch Manifest |publisher=SpaceX |url=http://www.spacex.com/launch_manifest.php |accessdate=31 May 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NASA Launch Schedule\">\n{{cite web |title=NASA's Consolidated Launch Schedule |publisher=NASA |url=http://www.nasa.gov/missions/highlights/schedule.html |accessdate=21 June 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NASAsept20\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/main/spacex-crs1-target.html |title=SpaceX, NASA Target Oct. 7 Launch For Resupply Mission To Space Station |date=20 September 2012 |publisher=NASA |accessdate=26 September 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Clark 18 May 2012\">\n{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=18 May 2012 |title=SpaceX's historic commercial mission is 'just a test flight' |publisher=SpaceFlightNow |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/003/120518commercial/ |accessdate=25 August 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=ClarkOct28>{{cite web |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121028splashdown/#.UI_fCIa_PKg |title=Return of the Dragon: Commercial craft back home |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=28 October 2012 |publisher=SpaceFlightNow |accessdate=30 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Clark 24 August 2012\">\n{{cite web |title=NASA ready for operational cargo flights by SpaceX |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=24 August 2012 |publisher=SpaceFlightNow |url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n1208/24cots/ |accessdate=25 August 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=SPACENOW10>{{cite web |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/falcon9/004/121010arrival/ |title=Dragon arrives at station with commercial delivery |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=10 October 2012 |publisher=SpaceFlightNow |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Orbcomm 25 May 2012\">\n{{cite press |title=Orbcomm Eagerly Awaits Launch of New Satellite on Next Falcon 9 |date=25 May 2012 |publisher=Space News |url=http://www.spacenews.com/satellite_telecom/120525-spacex-success-welcome-orbcomm.html |accessdate=28 May 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hartman 23 July 2012\">\n{{cite web |last=Hartman |first=Dan |date=23 July 2012 |title=International Space Station Program Status |publisher=NASA |url=http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/672214main_1-Hartman_July12_NAC_Final_508.pdf |accessdate=28 August 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sept29\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2012/09/falcon-9-hot-fires-engines-iss-prepares-dragons-arrival/ |title=Falcon 9 hot fires its engines as the ISS prepares for Dragon's arrival |last=Bergin |first=Chris |date=29 September 2012 |publisher=NASASpaceFlight (not associated with NASA) |accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AugustChris\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2012/08/spacex-conduct-successful-wdr-falcon-9/ |title=SpaceX conduct successful WDR on their latest Falcon 9 |last=Bergin |first=Chris |date=31 August 2012 |publisher=NASASpaceFlight (not associated with NASA) |accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|SpaceX CRS-1}}\n*[http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/living/launch/index.html SpaceX CRS-1 NASA page]\n*[http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/694166main_SpaceXCRS-1PressKit.pdf SpaceX CRS-1 Mission Press Kit (4 October 2012)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5I7loLnDYyU Video of Static Fire test - YouTube (spacexchannel)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tRTYh71D9P0 Video of Launch - YouTube (spacexchannel)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lg5vd_Gs0G4 Video of Approach, Grappling and Berthing of Dragon - YouTube (ReelNASA)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NAXBdt5gS_c Video of Hatch Opening - YouTube (NASATelevision)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W_bF6ZciBxQ Video of Dragon Splashdown - YouTube (spacexchannel)]\n\n{{Dragon spaceflights}}\n{{Falcon rocket launches}}\n{{Unmanned ISS resupply flights}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:CRS 001}}\n[[Category:SpaceX Dragon]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2012]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 2012]]\n[[Category:SpaceX payloads contracted by NASA]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "CRS-20", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRemainder of mission (11 to 28 October)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SpaceX_CRS-1"}
{"title_page": "Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!", "text_new": "{{ external media\n| width  = 210px\n| align  = right\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFUtDdgEYwk Original video]\n}}\n\"'''Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!'''\" ({{lang-ru|\u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439? \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f!}}, meaning \"Who are you? Hey, Goodbye!\") is a title of the [[viral video]], showing [[meykhana]] performance with repeating Russian [[Hook (music)|hook]] \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" by two brothers Intigam and Ehtiram Rustamov from [[Azerbaijan]]. The video was filmed on 5 November 2011 at a wedding in [[T\u0259ng\u0259rud|Tangarud]], [[Azerbaijan]] and was subsequently viewed over 10 million times on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFUtDdgEYwk| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439,\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f! (Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!)| publisher = [[YouTube]]| date = 2012-01-25| accessdate = 12 July 2012 }}</ref> It is sung in the form of [[flyting]] between Talysh and [[Baku]] groups in [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[Talysh language|Talysh]] and Russian. The video was also viewed over 10 million times at theinstv, the YouTube channel of Insanity TV.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GZrGyySwmbM| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439? \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f! :D_5.mp4.mp4| publisher = [[YouTube]]| date = 2012-05-23| accessdate = 30 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Political references ==\n[[File:Serzh Sargsyan Davay, do svidaniya!.jpg|thumb|300px|Poster with the crossed-out portrait of Armenian president [[Serzh Sargsyan]] with the famous line during the [[2013 Armenian presidential election protests]] ]]\n\nThe hook itself was popularized particularly by the Russian Car Owners Federation official Andrey Filin, who had wrote on [[Twitter]]: \"Tomorrow I'll hang a sign on my car: '[[Vladimir Putin|Putin]], who are you? See you, goodbye'. I'll make people smile\".<ref name=\"TMT\">{{cite news | url = http://www.themoscowtimes.com/mobile/article/459562.html| title = Video Inspires Anti-Putin Twitter Trend| newspaper = [[The Moscow Times]]| date = 31 May 2012| accessdate = 14 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFilin's phrase \"Putin, who are you? Come on, goodbye\" was in turn propagated by the press secretary of [[Ilya Ponomarev]] and by the Russian art group [[Voina|Voyna]]. The Russian [[hashtag]] #\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0442\u044b\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f (\"Putin, who are you? Come on, goodbye\") began spreading in Twitter on 29 May 2012<ref name=\"TMT\"/> and entered Twitter's worldwide trends the next day. The phrase \"Who are you? See you, goodbye\" later appeared on [[Picketing (protest)|picket]] banners in [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ntv.ru/novosti/305222/| script-title=ru:\u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| language=Russian|publisher = [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]]| accessdate = 18 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, a group of [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] opposition members used the phrase \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" targeting president [[Mikheil Saakashvili]] in a performance of their own, which they sang in [[Georgian language|Georgian]] and released online.<ref>[http://vesti.az/news/127918/D098_D0B3D180D183D0B7D0B8D0BDD181D0BAD0B8D0B5_D0BED0BFD0BFD0BED0B7D0B8D186D0B8D0BED0BDD0B5D180D18B_D0B2D0B7D18FD0BBD0B8_D0BDD0B0_D0B2D0BED0BED180D183D0B6D0B5D0BDD0B8D0B5_D182D0B2D0BED180D187D0B5D181D182D0B2D0BE_D0B0D0B7D0B5D180D0B1D0B0D0B9D0B4D0B6D0B0D0BDD181D0BAD0B8D185_D0BCD0B5D0B9D185D0B0D0BDD189D0B8D0BAD0BED0B2_ \u0418 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u044b \u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0430\u0437\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u0435\u0439\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0449\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432]. ''Vesti.az''. 27 August 2012.</ref> The phrase addressed to the Hungarian government was used on placards posted around [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]] during a protest at the Consulate of Hungary on 1 September 2012, upon the extradition of officer [[Ramil Safarov]], who had been convicted by a Hungarian court for murdering his Armenian counterpart in 2004.<ref>[http://www.argumenti.ru/world/2012/09/199662 Flag Burning by Hungarian Consulate]. AN Online. 1 September 2012.</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nThe hook \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" has been repeatedly [[remix]]ed and was [[Sampling (music)|sampled]] for [[dubstep]] and [[tech house]] [[Mashup (music)|mashup]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://muzofon.com/search/\u0422\u044b%20\u043a\u0442\u043e%20\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439%20\u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439%20\u0434\u043e%20\u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140921225021/http://muzofon.com/search/%D0%A2%D1%8B%20%D0%BA%D1%82%D0%BE%20%D1%82%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B9%20%D0%94%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%B9%20%D0%B4%D0%BE%20%D1%81%D0%B2%D0%B8%D0%B4%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F| url-status = dead| archive-date = 21 September 2014| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| publisher = Muzofon| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref> Russian rapper [[Timati]] sampled the hook for his [[diss song]] against [[Philipp Kirkorov]], with participants fashioning the dress style and locale of the original video.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M9RcdLCJkw4| title = #\u0414\u0410\u0412\u0410\u0419\u0414\u041e\u0421\u0412\u0418\u0414\u0410\u041d\u0418\u042f (OFFICIAL VIDEO)| publisher = YouTube| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref>  \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" is also the subject of one of the sketches of Russian ''Lego Life Show'' on YouTube. The phrase also influenced an article on the Russian sports news website Sportbox, which wrote about the \"unpleasing list with trendy title \"Who are you? See you, goodbye!\" in connection with the group stage of [[UEFA Euro 2012]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.sportbox.ru/Vidy_sporta/Futbol/Euro-2012/spbnews_NI315468_Ispaniya-Irlandiya-Davay-do-svidaniya| script-title=ru:\u0418\u0441\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u2013 \u0418\u0440\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u044f: \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f?| language=Russian|publisher = News.sportbox.ru| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref> The phrase \"Who are you? See you, goodbye!\" was also uttered by Russian sportcaster Viktor Gusev during a [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group D#Ukraine vs Sweden|Euro 2012 match between Sweden and Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.newsazerbaijan.ru/sport/20120612/297452302.html| script-title=ru:\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0413\u0443\u0441\u0435\u0432: \u0418\u0441\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0441\u043e\u043d, \"\u0442\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439, \u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f!\"| publisher = Newsazerbaijan| language=Russian|date=12 June 2012|accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Viral videos]]\n[[Category:YouTube videos]]\n[[Category:Russian words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 works]]\n[[Category:2011 in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in the 2010s]]\n", "text_old": "{{ external media\n| width  = 210px\n| align  = right\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFUtDdgEYwk Original video]\n}}\n\"'''Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!'''\" ({{lang-ru|\u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439? \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f!}}, meaning \"Who are you? Hey!, Goodbye!\") is a title of the [[viral video]], showing [[meykhana]] performance with repeating Russian [[Hook (music)|hook]] \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" by two brothers Intigam and Ehtiram Rustamov from [[Azerbaijan]]. The video was filmed on 5 November 2011 at a wedding in [[T\u0259ng\u0259rud|Tangarud]], [[Azerbaijan]] and was subsequently viewed over 10 million times on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFUtDdgEYwk| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439,\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f! (Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!)| publisher = [[YouTube]]| date = 2012-01-25| accessdate = 12 July 2012 }}</ref> It is sung in the form of [[flyting]] between Talysh and [[Baku]] groups in [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[Talysh language|Talysh]] and Russian. The video was also viewed over 10 million times at theinstv, the YouTube channel of Insanity TV.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GZrGyySwmbM| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439? \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f! :D_5.mp4.mp4| publisher = [[YouTube]]| date = 2012-05-23| accessdate = 30 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Political references ==\n[[File:Serzh Sargsyan Davay, do svidaniya!.jpg|thumb|300px|Poster with the crossed-out portrait of Armenian president [[Serzh Sargsyan]] with the famous line during the [[2013 Armenian presidential election protests]] ]]\n\nThe hook itself was popularized particularly by the Russian Car Owners Federation official Andrey Filin, who had wrote on [[Twitter]]: \"Tomorrow I'll hang a sign on my car: '[[Vladimir Putin|Putin]], who are you? See you, goodbye'. I'll make people smile\".<ref name=\"TMT\">{{cite news | url = http://www.themoscowtimes.com/mobile/article/459562.html| title = Video Inspires Anti-Putin Twitter Trend| newspaper = [[The Moscow Times]]| date = 31 May 2012| accessdate = 14 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFilin's phrase \"Putin, who are you? Come on, goodbye\" was in turn propagated by the press secretary of [[Ilya Ponomarev]] and by the Russian art group [[Voina|Voyna]]. The Russian [[hashtag]] #\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0442\u044b\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f (\"Putin, who are you? Come on, goodbye\") began spreading in Twitter on 29 May 2012<ref name=\"TMT\"/> and entered Twitter's worldwide trends the next day. The phrase \"Who are you? See you, goodbye\" later appeared on [[Picketing (protest)|picket]] banners in [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ntv.ru/novosti/305222/| script-title=ru:\u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| language=Russian|publisher = [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]]| accessdate = 18 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, a group of [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] opposition members used the phrase \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" targeting president [[Mikheil Saakashvili]] in a performance of their own, which they sang in [[Georgian language|Georgian]] and released online.<ref>[http://vesti.az/news/127918/D098_D0B3D180D183D0B7D0B8D0BDD181D0BAD0B8D0B5_D0BED0BFD0BFD0BED0B7D0B8D186D0B8D0BED0BDD0B5D180D18B_D0B2D0B7D18FD0BBD0B8_D0BDD0B0_D0B2D0BED0BED180D183D0B6D0B5D0BDD0B8D0B5_D182D0B2D0BED180D187D0B5D181D182D0B2D0BE_D0B0D0B7D0B5D180D0B1D0B0D0B9D0B4D0B6D0B0D0BDD181D0BAD0B8D185_D0BCD0B5D0B9D185D0B0D0BDD189D0B8D0BAD0BED0B2_ \u0418 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u044b \u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0430\u0437\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u0435\u0439\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0449\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432]. ''Vesti.az''. 27 August 2012.</ref> The phrase addressed to the Hungarian government was used on placards posted around [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]] during a protest at the Consulate of Hungary on 1 September 2012, upon the extradition of officer [[Ramil Safarov]], who had been convicted by a Hungarian court for murdering his Armenian counterpart in 2004.<ref>[http://www.argumenti.ru/world/2012/09/199662 Flag Burning by Hungarian Consulate]. AN Online. 1 September 2012.</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nThe hook \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" has been repeatedly [[remix]]ed and was [[Sampling (music)|sampled]] for [[dubstep]] and [[tech house]] [[Mashup (music)|mashup]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://muzofon.com/search/\u0422\u044b%20\u043a\u0442\u043e%20\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439%20\u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439%20\u0434\u043e%20\u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140921225021/http://muzofon.com/search/%D0%A2%D1%8B%20%D0%BA%D1%82%D0%BE%20%D1%82%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B9%20%D0%94%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%B9%20%D0%B4%D0%BE%20%D1%81%D0%B2%D0%B8%D0%B4%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F| url-status = dead| archive-date = 21 September 2014| title = \u0422\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f| publisher = Muzofon| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref> Russian rapper [[Timati]] sampled the hook for his [[diss song]] against [[Philipp Kirkorov]], with participants fashioning the dress style and locale of the original video.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M9RcdLCJkw4| title = #\u0414\u0410\u0412\u0410\u0419\u0414\u041e\u0421\u0412\u0418\u0414\u0410\u041d\u0418\u042f (OFFICIAL VIDEO)| publisher = YouTube| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref>  \"Ty kto takoy? Davay, do svidaniya!\" is also the subject of one of the sketches of Russian ''Lego Life Show'' on YouTube. The phrase also influenced an article on the Russian sports news website Sportbox, which wrote about the \"unpleasing list with trendy title \"Who are you? See you, goodbye!\" in connection with the group stage of [[UEFA Euro 2012]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.sportbox.ru/Vidy_sporta/Futbol/Euro-2012/spbnews_NI315468_Ispaniya-Irlandiya-Davay-do-svidaniya| script-title=ru:\u0418\u0441\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u2013 \u0418\u0440\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u044f: \u0414\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f?| language=Russian|publisher = News.sportbox.ru| accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref> The phrase \"Who are you? See you, goodbye!\" was also uttered by Russian sportcaster Viktor Gusev during a [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group D#Ukraine vs Sweden|Euro 2012 match between Sweden and Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.newsazerbaijan.ru/sport/20120612/297452302.html| script-title=ru:\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0413\u0443\u0441\u0435\u0432: \u0418\u0441\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0441\u043e\u043d, \"\u0442\u044b \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439, \u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0439, \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f!\"| publisher = Newsazerbaijan| language=Russian|date=12 June 2012|accessdate = 14 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Viral videos]]\n[[Category:YouTube videos]]\n[[Category:Russian words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 works]]\n[[Category:2011 in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in the 2010s]]\n", "name_user": "Zealander", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ty_kto_takoy%3F_Davay,_do_svidaniya!"}
{"title_page": "Ryan Jack", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish football player (born 1992)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ryan Jack\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| height =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1992|02|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Aberdeen]], Scotland\n| currentclub = [[Huns F.C.|Huns F.C.]]\n| clubnumber = 8\n| position = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 2000\u20132010\n| youthclubs1 = [[Aberdeen F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Aberdeen]]\n| years1 = 2010\u20132017\n| clubs1 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n| caps1 = 199\n| goals1 = 11\n| years2 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs2 = [[Huns F.C.|Huns]]\n| caps2 = 66\n| goals2 = 8<!--League games/goals only. Cup games go in Career statistics table-->\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132008\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2008\u20132009\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 7\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2009\u20132010\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 1\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2011\u20132014\n| nationalteam4 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 19\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| nationalyears5 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 3\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| club-update = 11 march 2020\n| ntupdate = 18:35, 16 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Ryan Jack''' (born 27 February 1992) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] for [[Huns F.C.|Huns]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].\n\nHe began his career at [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]], spending 17 years connected with the club across youth and senior categories and serving as club captain for two years. Jack left Aberdeen in 2017, signing for The Huns as a free agent.\n\n== Club career ==\n=== Aberdeen ===\nJack signed professional terms with Aberdeen in the summer of 2008,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/Article.aspx/743652 |title=Meet the young guns ready for action |publisher=Evening Express |date=18 July 2008 |accessdate=23 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726215620/http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/Article.aspx/743652 |archivedate=26 July 2011  }}</ref> having been part of his hometown club's [[youth system|youth academy]] since the age of eight.<ref name=contract>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15281798.stm|title=Midfielder Ryan Jack extends Aberdeen contract|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 October 2011|accessdate=12 October 2011}}</ref> He made his first team league debut for the club against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in September 2010<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/Article.aspx/1931835 |title=Aberdeen FC rookie Ryan ready for Rangers' \u00a312m men |publisher=Evening Express |date=24 September 2010 |accessdate=23 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726215648/http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/Article.aspx/1931835 |archivedate=26 July 2011  }}</ref> and soon became a regular in the first team.\n\nIn January 2011 he scored his first goal for Aberdeen against [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]], which was voted as the club's Goal of the Season for 2010\u201311.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20110513/today-at-pittodrie-a-round-up_2212158_2359769 |title=Today at Pittodrie |publisher=Aberdeen FC |accessdate=10 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606113248/http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20110513/today-at-pittodrie-a-round-up_2212158_2359769 |archive-date=6 June 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> A week later, he came on as a substitute in the [[2010\u201311 Scottish League Cup#Semi-finals|Scottish Cup semi-final]] at [[Hampden Park]], a 4\u20131 defeat to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_cups/9378059.stm|title=Aberdeen 1\u20134 Celtic|date=29 January 2011|publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nJack signed a new contract with Aberdeen in October 2011.<ref name=contract /> On 13 December 2011 in a [[Scottish Premier League|SPL]] fixture against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]], he scored a goal from the halfway line to put his team 2\u20130 up after opposing goalkeeper [[Peter Enckelman]] miskicked a clearance. The match ended 2\u20131 to Aberdeen, with Jack's winner helping the Dons move up to ninth in the table.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16044918.stm|title=St Johnstone 1\u20132 Aberdeen|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 December 2011|accessdate=13 December 2011 | first=Clive |last=Lindsay}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Jack signed a three-year deal at Aberdeen, keeping him at the club until 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Midfielder Ryan Jack signs new contract with Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23000667|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 June 2013|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> He subsequently played a pivotal role in Aberdeen's season, helping them into the [[2013\u201314 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] semi-final, but was injured in January in a league match at [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]. and was ruled out for around six weeks, missing the semi-final with St Johnstone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aberdeen: Injured Ryan Jack to miss League Cup semi-final|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25910641|publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 January 2014|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> He had returned by the time of [[2014 Scottish League Cup Final|the final of the competition]], playing all 120 minutes as his club overcame Inverness CT in a penalty shoot-out.<ref name=lc14/> Jack did participate in a semi-final during [[2013\u201314 in Scottish football|the campaign]] in the [[2013\u201314 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]], again facing St Johnstone, but was on the losing side on that occasion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scottish Cup: Stevie May the hero in St Johnstone win over Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26908707|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 April 2014|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 January 2015, Jack was named as [[List of Scottish Professional Football League monthly award winners#2014\u201315 season|SPFL Player of the Month]] for December 2014.<ref name=\"potm\">{{cite web|title=SPFL Awards December Manager and Player|url=http://www.afc.co.uk/news/5563.php|publisher=Aberdeen F.C.|date=11 January 2015|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref> Two weeks later, he missed out on another League Cup final appearance as his team were beaten in [[2014\u201315 Scottish League Cup#Semi-final|the semis]] by [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]].<ref>{{cite news| url =   https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30963450 | title =  Dundee Utd 2\u20131 Aberdeen | publisher = BBC Sport| date =   31 January 2015| accessdate = 28 January 2018}}</ref> On 20 May 2015, he signed a one-year extension to his contract, keeping him at Aberdeen until the end of the 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ryan Jack signs new deal at Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32815770|publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 May 2015|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> On 24 June 2015, Jack was named captain for the [[2015\u201316 Aberdeen F.C. season|2015\u201316]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ryan is the new Dons captain|url=http://www.afc.co.uk/news/6371.php|publisher=Aberdeen F.C.|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter much speculation that he would move on, Jack left Aberdeen in May 2017 when his contract expired, having played almost 250 times for the ''Dons''. His last game was the [[2017 Scottish Cup Final]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40113519 |title=Aberdeen: Ash Taylor & Lawrence Shankland join players leaving Pittodrie |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 May 2017 |accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> earlier in the season he had also led out the team in the [[2016 Scottish League Cup Final (November)|League Cup final]],<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/11/27/aberdeen-0-celtic-3-brendan-rodgers-wins-first-trophy-spark/ |title=Aberdeen 0 Celtic 3: Brendan Rodgers wins first trophy to spark talk of a treble|date=27 November 2016|work=Telegraph|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> with both showpiece matches lost to Celtic.\n\n=== Rangers ===\nJack signed a three-year contract with [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] on 1 June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40111528 |title=Rangers: former Aberdeen captain Ryan Jack completes move to Ibrox |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2017 |accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> Upon signing, the former Aberdeen captain said that he was a huge Rangers fan growing up and that it was an \"honour and a privilege\" to join the club he supported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/its-great-to-be-here-2/ |title=It's Great To Be Here |first=Neil |last=Smith| publisher=Rangers.co.uk |date=1 June 2017 |accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> He made his debut for Rangers against [[Luxembourg]]ish side [[FC Progr\u00e8s Niederkorn|Progr\u00e8s Niederkorn]] in the 1st qualifying round of the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League]] on 29 June 2017, a tie which Rangers lost 2\u20131 on aggregate after [[Progr\u00e8s Niederkorn 2\u20130 Rangers|losing 2\u20130]] away from home.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rangers 1\u20130 Progres Niederkorn|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40410727|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn Rangers' first visit to Aberdeen since his move, Jack started the game but was sent off in the second half for a bad tackle, although his team won the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen 1 Rangers 2: Derek McInnes remains favourite for Ibrox job despite losing dress rehearsal at Pittodrie|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/12/03/aberdeen-1-rangers-2derek-mcinnes-remains-favourite-ibrox-job/|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=3 December 2017|accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref> It was the fourth [[penalty card#Red card|red card]] in the [[2017\u201318 Rangers F.C. season|2017\u201318]] season (two were rescinded after reviews).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40835318 |title=Rangers 2\u20133 Hibernian |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 August 2017 |accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41356615 |title=Hamilton Academical 1\u20134 Rangers |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 September 2017 |accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41661422 |title=Rangers 1\u20131 Kilmarnock |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 October 2017 |accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref> In January 2018, Rangers confirmed that Jack required surgery on a knee injury sustained in a match the previous month, ruling him out of action for some time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/rangers/ryan-jack-needs-surgery-on-knee-injury-graeme-murty-confirms-1-4673335 |title=Ryan Jack needs surgery on knee injury, Graeme Murty confirms |work=The Scotsman |date=26 January 2018|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nJack signed a new contract with Rangers in December 2018, due to run until the end of the 2020\u201321 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46645175 |title=Rangers: Midfielder Ryan Jack signs new Ibrox deal until 2021 |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 December 2018 |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> On 29 December, he scored his first Rangers goal in the [[Old Firm]] derby against Celtic, a match which Rangers won 1\u20130.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46656785|title=Rangers 1\u20130 Celtic: Brendan Rodgers suffers first Old Firm defeat|date=29 December 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019 he signed a new four-year contract with the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50147343|title=Ryan Jack: Rangers midfielder extends contract until 2023|date=22 October 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n== International career ==\nJack has represented Scotland at [[Scotland national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[Scotland national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[Scotland national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21 level]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=289&playerID=42198&squadID=17 |title=Ryan Jack profile |publisher=Scottish Football Association |accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref> He captained the Under-21 side and is on the top ten list for appearances at this level. In May 2013, he received a call-up to the full Scotland squad for the game against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22607488 |title=Scotland: Leigh Griffiths & Tony Watt called up for Croatia match |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nJack eventually made his full Scotland debut in a friendly against [[Netherlands national football team|the Netherlands]] in November 2017, by which time he had moved from formative club Aberdeen to Rangers. The match happened to take place in Aberdeen, and in the opening stages he was booed whenever he touched the ball by some of the crowd, due to the [[Aberdeen F.C.-Rangers F.C. rivalry|rivalry between those clubs]] and the ill-feeling his transfer had stirred; other fans responded to this by cheering and applauding him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/scotland/rangers-ryan-jack-booed-on-return-to-pittodrie-with-scotland-1-4609487 |title=Rangers' Ryan Jack booed on return to Pittodrie with Scotland |newspaper=The Scotsman |publisher= |date=9 November 2017 |accessdate=10 November 2017 }}</ref>\n\nJack made his first competitive start for Scotland in November 2019, forming a midfield partnership with [[Callum McGregor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50496298 |title=Rangers' Ryan Jack deserves to continue partnership with Celtic rival - Kenny Miller |website= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 November 2019 |accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career statistics ==\n{{Updated|15 December 2019}}<ref>{{soccerway|ryan-jack/46472|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Scottish Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|[[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Aberdeen F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2010|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|30||1||4||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||37||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Aberdeen F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2011|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|31||3||4||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||37||3\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Aberdeen F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2012|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|18||0||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||19||0\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Aberdeen F.C. season|2013\u201314]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2013|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Scottish Premiership]]\n|34||2||3||0||4||0||colspan=2|\u2014||41||2\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Aberdeen F.C. season|2014\u201315]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2014|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|32||3||1||0||3||0||6<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\">Appearances in the [[UEFA Europa League]]</ref>||0||42||3\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Aberdeen F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2015|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|28||0||0||0||1||0||6<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||0||35||0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Aberdeen F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2016|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|26||2||4||0||3||0||6<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||0||39||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!199!!11!!16!!0!!17!!0!!18!!0!!250!!11\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Rangers F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2017|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Scottish Premiership\n|17||0||0||0||2||0||2<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||0||21||0\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Rangers F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2018|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n|30||4||5||0||1||0||10<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||0||46||4\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Rangers F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n|11||4||0||0||3||0||13<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||1||24||5\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!58!!8!!5!!0!!6!!0!!25!!1!!94!!9\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!257!!19!!21!!0!!23!!0!!43!!1!!344!!20\n|}\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n== Honours ==\n=== Club ===\n;Aberdeen\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[2014 Scottish League Cup Final|2013\u201314]]<ref name=lc14>{{cite web|title=Aberdeen 0\u20130 Inverness CT (Aberdeen win 4\u20132 on penalties)|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26502621|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Campbell|first=Andy|date=16 March 2014|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Individual ===\n*[[List of Scottish Professional Football League monthly award winners#2014\u201315 season|SPFL Player of the Month]]: December 2014<ref name=\"potm\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{soccerbase|id=48897|name=Ryan Jack}}\n* [http://www.afcheritage.org/Team/CurrentSquad/player_show.cfm?player_id=807 Profile and stats] at ''AFC Heritage Trust''\n\n{{Rangers F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jack, Ryan}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scottish football player (born 1992)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ryan Jack\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| height =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1992|02|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Aberdeen]], Scotland\n| currentclub = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| clubnumber = 8\n| position = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 2000\u20132010\n| youthclubs1 = [[Aberdeen F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Aberdeen]]\n| years1 = 2010\u20132017\n| clubs1 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n| caps1 = 199\n| goals1 = 11\n| years2 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs2 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| caps2 = 66\n| goals2 = 8<!--League games/goals only. Cup games go in Career statistics table-->\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132008\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2008\u20132009\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 7\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2009\u20132010\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 1\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2011\u20132014\n| nationalteam4 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 19\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| nationalyears5 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 3\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| club-update = 11 march 2020\n| ntupdate = 18:35, 16 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Ryan Jack''' (born 27 February 1992) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].\n\nHe began his career at [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]], spending 17 years connected with the club across youth and senior categories and serving as club captain for two years. Jack left Aberdeen in 2017, signing for Rangers as a free agent.\n\n== Club career ==\n=== Aberdeen ===\nJack signed professional terms with Aberdeen in the summer of 2008,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/Article.aspx/743652 |title=Meet the young guns ready for action |publisher=Evening Express |date=18 July 2008 |accessdate=23 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726215620/http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/Article.aspx/743652 |archivedate=26 July 2011  }}</ref> having been part of his hometown club's [[youth system|youth academy]] since the age of eight.<ref name=contract>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15281798.stm|title=Midfielder Ryan Jack extends Aberdeen contract|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 October 2011|accessdate=12 October 2011}}</ref> He made his first team league debut for the club against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in September 2010<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/Article.aspx/1931835 |title=Aberdeen FC rookie Ryan ready for Rangers' \u00a312m men |publisher=Evening Express |date=24 September 2010 |accessdate=23 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726215648/http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/Article.aspx/1931835 |archivedate=26 July 2011  }}</ref> and soon became a regular in the first team.\n\nIn January 2011 he scored his first goal for Aberdeen against [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]], which was voted as the club's Goal of the Season for 2010\u201311.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20110513/today-at-pittodrie-a-round-up_2212158_2359769 |title=Today at Pittodrie |publisher=Aberdeen FC |accessdate=10 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606113248/http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20110513/today-at-pittodrie-a-round-up_2212158_2359769 |archive-date=6 June 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> A week later, he came on as a substitute in the [[2010\u201311 Scottish League Cup#Semi-finals|Scottish Cup semi-final]] at [[Hampden Park]], a 4\u20131 defeat to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_cups/9378059.stm|title=Aberdeen 1\u20134 Celtic|date=29 January 2011|publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nJack signed a new contract with Aberdeen in October 2011.<ref name=contract /> On 13 December 2011 in a [[Scottish Premier League|SPL]] fixture against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]], he scored a goal from the halfway line to put his team 2\u20130 up after opposing goalkeeper [[Peter Enckelman]] miskicked a clearance. The match ended 2\u20131 to Aberdeen, with Jack's winner helping the Dons move up to ninth in the table.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16044918.stm|title=St Johnstone 1\u20132 Aberdeen|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 December 2011|accessdate=13 December 2011 | first=Clive |last=Lindsay}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Jack signed a three-year deal at Aberdeen, keeping him at the club until 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Midfielder Ryan Jack signs new contract with Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23000667|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 June 2013|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> He subsequently played a pivotal role in Aberdeen's season, helping them into the [[2013\u201314 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] semi-final, but was injured in January in a league match at [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]. and was ruled out for around six weeks, missing the semi-final with St Johnstone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aberdeen: Injured Ryan Jack to miss League Cup semi-final|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25910641|publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 January 2014|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> He had returned by the time of [[2014 Scottish League Cup Final|the final of the competition]], playing all 120 minutes as his club overcame Inverness CT in a penalty shoot-out.<ref name=lc14/> Jack did participate in a semi-final during [[2013\u201314 in Scottish football|the campaign]] in the [[2013\u201314 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]], again facing St Johnstone, but was on the losing side on that occasion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scottish Cup: Stevie May the hero in St Johnstone win over Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26908707|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 April 2014|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 January 2015, Jack was named as [[List of Scottish Professional Football League monthly award winners#2014\u201315 season|SPFL Player of the Month]] for December 2014.<ref name=\"potm\">{{cite web|title=SPFL Awards December Manager and Player|url=http://www.afc.co.uk/news/5563.php|publisher=Aberdeen F.C.|date=11 January 2015|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref> Two weeks later, he missed out on another League Cup final appearance as his team were beaten in [[2014\u201315 Scottish League Cup#Semi-final|the semis]] by [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]].<ref>{{cite news| url =   https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30963450 | title =  Dundee Utd 2\u20131 Aberdeen | publisher = BBC Sport| date =   31 January 2015| accessdate = 28 January 2018}}</ref> On 20 May 2015, he signed a one-year extension to his contract, keeping him at Aberdeen until the end of the 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ryan Jack signs new deal at Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32815770|publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 May 2015|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref> On 24 June 2015, Jack was named captain for the [[2015\u201316 Aberdeen F.C. season|2015\u201316]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ryan is the new Dons captain|url=http://www.afc.co.uk/news/6371.php|publisher=Aberdeen F.C.|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter much speculation that he would move on, Jack left Aberdeen in May 2017 when his contract expired, having played almost 250 times for the ''Dons''. His last game was the [[2017 Scottish Cup Final]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40113519 |title=Aberdeen: Ash Taylor & Lawrence Shankland join players leaving Pittodrie |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 May 2017 |accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> earlier in the season he had also led out the team in the [[2016 Scottish League Cup Final (November)|League Cup final]],<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/11/27/aberdeen-0-celtic-3-brendan-rodgers-wins-first-trophy-spark/ |title=Aberdeen 0 Celtic 3: Brendan Rodgers wins first trophy to spark talk of a treble|date=27 November 2016|work=Telegraph|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> with both showpiece matches lost to Celtic.\n\n=== Rangers ===\nJack signed a three-year contract with [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] on 1 June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40111528 |title=Rangers: former Aberdeen captain Ryan Jack completes move to Ibrox |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2017 |accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> Upon signing, the former Aberdeen captain said that he was a huge Rangers fan growing up and that it was an \"honour and a privilege\" to join the club he supported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/its-great-to-be-here-2/ |title=It's Great To Be Here |first=Neil |last=Smith| publisher=Rangers.co.uk |date=1 June 2017 |accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> He made his debut for Rangers against [[Luxembourg]]ish side [[FC Progr\u00e8s Niederkorn|Progr\u00e8s Niederkorn]] in the 1st qualifying round of the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League]] on 29 June 2017, a tie which Rangers lost 2\u20131 on aggregate after [[Progr\u00e8s Niederkorn 2\u20130 Rangers|losing 2\u20130]] away from home.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rangers 1\u20130 Progres Niederkorn|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40410727|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn Rangers' first visit to Aberdeen since his move, Jack started the game but was sent off in the second half for a bad tackle, although his team won the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen 1 Rangers 2: Derek McInnes remains favourite for Ibrox job despite losing dress rehearsal at Pittodrie|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/12/03/aberdeen-1-rangers-2derek-mcinnes-remains-favourite-ibrox-job/|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=3 December 2017|accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref> It was the fourth [[penalty card#Red card|red card]] in the [[2017\u201318 Rangers F.C. season|2017\u201318]] season (two were rescinded after reviews).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40835318 |title=Rangers 2\u20133 Hibernian |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 August 2017 |accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41356615 |title=Hamilton Academical 1\u20134 Rangers |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 September 2017 |accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41661422 |title=Rangers 1\u20131 Kilmarnock |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 October 2017 |accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref> In January 2018, Rangers confirmed that Jack required surgery on a knee injury sustained in a match the previous month, ruling him out of action for some time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/rangers/ryan-jack-needs-surgery-on-knee-injury-graeme-murty-confirms-1-4673335 |title=Ryan Jack needs surgery on knee injury, Graeme Murty confirms |work=The Scotsman |date=26 January 2018|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nJack signed a new contract with Rangers in December 2018, due to run until the end of the 2020\u201321 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46645175 |title=Rangers: Midfielder Ryan Jack signs new Ibrox deal until 2021 |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 December 2018 |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> On 29 December, he scored his first Rangers goal in the [[Old Firm]] derby against Celtic, a match which Rangers won 1\u20130.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46656785|title=Rangers 1\u20130 Celtic: Brendan Rodgers suffers first Old Firm defeat|date=29 December 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019 he signed a new four-year contract with the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50147343|title=Ryan Jack: Rangers midfielder extends contract until 2023|date=22 October 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n== International career ==\nJack has represented Scotland at [[Scotland national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[Scotland national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[Scotland national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21 level]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=289&playerID=42198&squadID=17 |title=Ryan Jack profile |publisher=Scottish Football Association |accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref> He captained the Under-21 side and is on the top ten list for appearances at this level. In May 2013, he received a call-up to the full Scotland squad for the game against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22607488 |title=Scotland: Leigh Griffiths & Tony Watt called up for Croatia match |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nJack eventually made his full Scotland debut in a friendly against [[Netherlands national football team|the Netherlands]] in November 2017, by which time he had moved from formative club Aberdeen to Rangers. The match happened to take place in Aberdeen, and in the opening stages he was booed whenever he touched the ball by some of the crowd, due to the [[Aberdeen F.C.-Rangers F.C. rivalry|rivalry between those clubs]] and the ill-feeling his transfer had stirred; other fans responded to this by cheering and applauding him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/scotland/rangers-ryan-jack-booed-on-return-to-pittodrie-with-scotland-1-4609487 |title=Rangers' Ryan Jack booed on return to Pittodrie with Scotland |newspaper=The Scotsman |publisher= |date=9 November 2017 |accessdate=10 November 2017 }}</ref>\n\nJack made his first competitive start for Scotland in November 2019, forming a midfield partnership with [[Callum McGregor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50496298 |title=Rangers' Ryan Jack deserves to continue partnership with Celtic rival - Kenny Miller |website= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 November 2019 |accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career statistics ==\n{{Updated|15 December 2019}}<ref>{{soccerway|ryan-jack/46472|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Scottish Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|[[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Aberdeen F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2010|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|30||1||4||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||37||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Aberdeen F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2011|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|31||3||4||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||37||3\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Aberdeen F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2012|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|18||0||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||19||0\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Aberdeen F.C. season|2013\u201314]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2013|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Scottish Premiership]]\n|34||2||3||0||4||0||colspan=2|\u2014||41||2\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Aberdeen F.C. season|2014\u201315]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2014|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|32||3||1||0||3||0||6<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\">Appearances in the [[UEFA Europa League]]</ref>||0||42||3\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Aberdeen F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2015|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|28||0||0||0||1||0||6<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||0||35||0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Aberdeen F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2016|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|26||2||4||0||3||0||6<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||0||39||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!199!!11!!16!!0!!17!!0!!18!!0!!250!!11\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Rangers F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2017|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Scottish Premiership\n|17||0||0||0||2||0||2<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||0||21||0\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Rangers F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2018|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n|30||4||5||0||1||0||10<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||0||46||4\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Rangers F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|48897|2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n|11||4||0||0||3||0||13<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UEL\"/>||1||24||5\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!58!!8!!5!!0!!6!!0!!25!!1!!94!!9\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!257!!19!!21!!0!!23!!0!!43!!1!!344!!20\n|}\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n== Honours ==\n=== Club ===\n;Aberdeen\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[2014 Scottish League Cup Final|2013\u201314]]<ref name=lc14>{{cite web|title=Aberdeen 0\u20130 Inverness CT (Aberdeen win 4\u20132 on penalties)|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26502621|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Campbell|first=Andy|date=16 March 2014|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Individual ===\n*[[List of Scottish Professional Football League monthly award winners#2014\u201315 season|SPFL Player of the Month]]: December 2014<ref name=\"potm\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{soccerbase|id=48897|name=Ryan Jack}}\n* [http://www.afcheritage.org/Team/CurrentSquad/player_show.cfm?player_id=807 Profile and stats] at ''AFC Heritage Trust''\n\n{{Rangers F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jack, Ryan}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "90.253.53.211", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryan_Jack"}
{"title_page": "Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham", "text_new": "'''[[:he:\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea_\u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8_\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|Yeshiva Yerucham]]'''\n\n'''Yeshivat Hesder Yerucham''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd}}) is a [[Hesder|hesder yeshiva]] located in the development town of [[Yeruham]], [[Israel]]. It was founded in 1993 and currently there are over 220 students<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />. It is known for its high level of learning and for being one of the most serious hesder yeshivas in Israel. [[File:Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham.jpg|thumbnail|A picture of the outside of Yeshivat Hesder Yerucham. ]]\n==History==\n[[File:Inside the beis medresh of the yeshiva.png|thumb|Inside the beis medresh of the yeshiva]]In the early 1970s, a group of [[Religious Zionism|Religious Zionists]] settled in Yeruham with the goal of imporving the south of Israel, and helping to increase the quality of life for the residents of Yerucham.  Over time, the group grew in number and expanded its activities by taking on educational responsibilities as well. After establishing \"Midreshet B'Yahad\", a Seminar Center of Judaism, Society and Zionism Studies, the group realized the need for a [[yeshiva]] as the next step in strengthening the existing projects by bringing youth to Yeruham.\n\nThe leader of this group, Shmuel Friedman Ben-Shalom, approached [[:he:\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5_\u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2|Rabbi Eliyhau Blumenzweig]], who at the time taught at [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]], with a proposition to be the Rosh Yeshiva, which he accepted. The yeshiva subsequently opened its doors in 1993<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kipa.co.il/%D7%91%D7%A8%D7%A0%D7%96%D7%94/943418-%D7%99%D7%A9%D7%99%D7%91%D7%AA-%D7%94%D7%94%D7%A1%D7%93%D7%A8-%D7%91%D7%99%D7%A8%D7%95%D7%97%D7%9D-%D7%97%D7%92%D7%92%D7%94-%D7%97%D7%A6%D7%99-%D7%99%D7%95%D7%91%D7%9C/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd \u05d7\u05d2\u05d2\u05d4 \u05d7\u05e6\u05d9 \u05d9\u05d5\u05d1\u05dc|date=2019-07-08|website=\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|language=he|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kipa.co.il/%D7%99%D7%94%D7%93%D7%95%D7%AA/%d7%99%d7%a9%d7%99%d7%91%d7%aa-%d7%99%d7%a8%d7%95%d7%97%d7%9d-%d7%97%d7%95%d7%92%d7%92%d7%aa-20-%d7%a9%d7%a0%d7%95%d7%aa-%d7%aa%d7%95%d7%a8%d7%94/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd \u05d7\u05d5\u05d2\u05d2\u05ea 20 \u05e9\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4|date=2012-08-29|website=\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|language=he|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/index.php?lang=he|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>.  \n\nToday, the yeshiva is considered to be one of the most serious hesder yeshivas in the country.\n\n==Curriculum==\n[[File:Yeshivat HaHesder Yeruham Old Building.jpg|thumb|Lunch room of the Yeshiva]]\nYeshivat HaHesder Yerucham emphasizes the importance of learning [[Talmud]] in depth, specifically through applying the [[Brisker method|Brisker Method]]. A typical day in Yeshiva will include two sessions of intensive Talmud study (''iyun'') and one of extensive study (''bekiut''). \n\nShachris at the Yeshiva is at 6:30am, followed by halachah seder until 8:00am. Breakfast is from 8:00am-8:30am. After breakfast is morning seder, which is typically gemara iyun, and it goes from 8:30am-1:00pm. Following morning seder is lunch and a break from 1:00pm-3pm. Mincha is at 3:00pm, followed by afternoon seder, from about 3:20pm-7:30pm. Afternoon seder consists of more iyun gemara, followed by a couple hours of emmunah. Many of the students use the entire afternoon seder for learning machshava, tanach, mussar, and emmunah. From 7:30pm-8:00pm is Maariv, followed by supper from 8:00pm-8:30pm. Night seder consists of learning bekiut, and it goes from 8:30pm until at least 11:00pm, although there is no given time for night seder to end, and many students learn until much later.[[File:Hayeshiva.jpg|thumb|Lunch room of the Yeshiva]]'''Daily Schedule''': \n\nShachrit: 6:30am-8:00am\n\nBreakfast: 8:00am-8:30am\n\nMorning seder: 8:30am-1:00pm\n\nLunch/break: 1:00pm-3:00pm\n\nMincha: 3:00pm-3:20pm\n\nAfternoon seder: 3:20pm-7:30pm\n\nSupper: 7:30pm-8:00pm\n\nMarriv: 8:00pm-8:30pm \n\nNight seder: 8:30pm-11:00pm (or later)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/26/46/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|last=|first=|date=|website=www.yhy.co.il|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of the afternoon seder, the yeshiva guides its students to base their perspective upon the teachings of [[Yehuda Halevi|Rabbi Yehuda Halevi]] and the [[Judah Loew ben Bezalel|Maharal of Prague]] in accordance with the ideology of [[Abraham Isaac Kook]], as is often customary in Religious Zionist yeshivas. With the goal of educating students to deal independently with the challenges they face living as an observant Jews in modern time in mind, the yeshiva encourages a broader study of Biblical, rabbinic, and other classical and modern sources. Hence, the yeshiva curriculum contains weekly classes in [[Tanakh]], [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Hasidic philosophy]], and the works of Jewish scholars such as [[Maimonides]], [[Nachmanides]], [[Moshe Chaim Luzzatto]], [[Joseph B. Soloveitchik]], [[Abraham Isaac Kook]] and many more.\n\n==Educational approach==\nThe yeshiva educates its students to be aware of their surroundings and attentive to the needs of society in general. The yeshiva believes that the keys to solving Israel\u2019s socioeconomic gaps lie in integration and education. All the students volunteer in the community mainly in the field of education. Many of the yeshiva's alumni settle in Yeruham instead of heading to the country's central cities.\n\nThe yeshiva also promotes other programs, among them:\n* ''Ye'adim'' (goals) - Concern of the Ethiopian Jewry in Israel's situation led Yerucham students to create a leadership training program for Ethiopian students with the intention of their returning to their communities. During the 5 years of Hesder the students synchronize their full Yeshiva studies with a [[Bachelor of Education|B.Ed.]] degree in [[Herzog College]].\n* Young Study Partners - First and second year students dedicate 2 hours weekly to studying Torah subjects with children from the local elementary school. They also serve as positive role models for the local youth and look to form a connection with their families.\n* Charity Fund - The goal of the Fund is to help the needy of Yeruham become self-sufficient and better managers of their money. The Fund uses the cooperation of the local welfare and professional financial advisors to this end.\n* ''B'levav Shalem'' Yeshiva High School \u2013 Because of the lack of high quality religious high schools in the [[Negev]], and as a part of the integration program the Hesder Yeshiva believes in, it was decided by alumni, residents of Yerucham, to open a Yeshiva High School for the local and general population.\n\n==Educational staff==\n[[File:\u05d4\u05e8\u05d1 \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2.JPG|thumb|Rabbi Blumenzweig]]\nIn addition to [[:he:\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5_\u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2|Rabbi Blumenzweig]], the other rabbis who teach in the Yeshiva are  Rabbi [[Uriel Eitam]], Rabbi Chaim Wolfson, Rabbi Shai Gnizi, Rabbi Shmuel Gleizer, Rabbi Achiya Ben Pazi, Rabbi Asher Weiss, Rabbi Ido Heber, Rabbi Shmuel Ariel, and Rabbi Elyakim Sharir<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/33/51/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd - \u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>. Rabbi Gnizi, Rabbi Gleizer, and Rabbi Ben Pazi all  began as students in the yeshiva. There are also rabbis who come from afar to give weekly classes, such as Rabbi Eliyahu Bazak, Rabbi Meir Kahana. Previously there were other teachers who have since left. These include [[:he:\u05de\u05d9\u05db\u05d0\u05dc \u05d0\u05d1\u05e8\u05d4\u05dd|Rabbi Dr. Michael Abraham]], Rabbi Ehud Barzilai, Rabbi Yair Ya'acobi (who is now serving as the rosh yeshiva of yerucham's relgious highschool \"balbash\"), Rabbi Avi Luria, Rabbis Yoseph Elitzor, and Rabbi Nir Weinberg (who left to establish and head the Hazor'im Yeshiva High-School in the lower Galilee)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/33/51/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd - \u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hesder]]\n*[[Yeshiva]]\n*[[Yerucham]] \n*[[Torah]] \n*[[Israel]] \n*[[Gemara]]\n*[[Brisker method]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.yhy.co.il Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham] (Hebrew)\n*[http://beyachad.dsites.co.il/HTMLs/Home.aspx Midreshet Beyahad] (Hebrew)\n\n==Yeshiva's publications==\nHere are a some of the publications from the yeshivas collective student body that have come out over the past number of years: \n\n*''Kutanot Or'' (Coats of Light) - \"A Jewish Perspective on the meaning of [[modesty]] and its value\", collection of essays edited by Yeshiva's students.\n*''Mimidbar Matana'' (A Present From The Desert) - A monthly newsletter which is sent out to students in the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] and alumni.\n*''Meisharim'' (Righteous) - A journal of articles on a variety of Torah topics, written by the students and teachers, published annually by the Yeshiva.\n*''Hahazit ShebaOref'' (The Home-Front Front) - A collection of essays dealing with the trials and challenges of a non-combat soldier. The book\u2019s intention is to answer some of the questions that soldiers serving in non-field units, such as the importance of their service, and [[Halakha|halakhic]] perspective on different situations.\n\nMany of the rabbis that teach in the yeshiva have also published a number of sefarim. {{Orthodox yeshivot in Israel}}{{Coord|30.9853882|N|34.9274340|E|source:hewiki_region:IL_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title}}[[Category:Yeshivot hesder|Yerucham]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Israel]]\n\n== Bibliography ==\n<references responsive=\"0\" />\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeshivat_Hesder_Yerucham}}\n", "text_old": "'''[[:he:\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea_\u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8_\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|Yeshiva Yerucham]]'''\n\n'''Yeshivat Hesder Yerucham''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd}}) is a [[Hesder|hesder yeshiva]] located in the development town of [[Yeruham]], [[Israel]]. It was founded in 1993 and currently there are over 220 students<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />. It is known for its high level of learning and for being one of the most serious hesder yeshivas in Israel. [[File:Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham.jpg|thumbnail|A picture of the outside of Yeshivat Hesder Yerucham. ]]\n==History==\n[[File:Inside the beis medresh of the yeshiva.png|thumb|Inside the beis medresh of the yeshiva]]In the early 1970s, a group of [[Religious Zionism|Religious Zionists]] settled in Yeruham with the goal of imporving the south of Israel, and helping to increase the quality of life for the residents of Yerucham.  Over time, the group grew in number and expanded its activities by taking on educational responsibilities as well. After establishing \"Midreshet B'Yahad\", a Seminar Center of Judaism, Society and Zionism Studies, the group realized the need for a [[yeshiva]] as the next step in strengthening the existing projects by bringing youth to Yeruham.\n\nThe leader of this group, Shmuel Friedman Ben-Shalom, approached [[:he:\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5_\u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2|Rabbi Eliyhau Blumenzweig]], who at the time taught at [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]], with a proposition to be the Rosh Yeshiva, which he accepted. The yeshiva subsequently opened its doors in 1993<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kipa.co.il/%D7%91%D7%A8%D7%A0%D7%96%D7%94/943418-%D7%99%D7%A9%D7%99%D7%91%D7%AA-%D7%94%D7%94%D7%A1%D7%93%D7%A8-%D7%91%D7%99%D7%A8%D7%95%D7%97%D7%9D-%D7%97%D7%92%D7%92%D7%94-%D7%97%D7%A6%D7%99-%D7%99%D7%95%D7%91%D7%9C/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd \u05d7\u05d2\u05d2\u05d4 \u05d7\u05e6\u05d9 \u05d9\u05d5\u05d1\u05dc|date=2019-07-08|website=\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|language=he|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kipa.co.il/%D7%99%D7%94%D7%93%D7%95%D7%AA/%d7%99%d7%a9%d7%99%d7%91%d7%aa-%d7%99%d7%a8%d7%95%d7%97%d7%9d-%d7%97%d7%95%d7%92%d7%92%d7%aa-20-%d7%a9%d7%a0%d7%95%d7%aa-%d7%aa%d7%95%d7%a8%d7%94/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd \u05d7\u05d5\u05d2\u05d2\u05ea 20 \u05e9\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4|date=2012-08-29|website=\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|language=he|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/index.php?lang=he|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>.  \n\nToday, the yeshiva is considered to be one of the most serious hesder yeshivas in the country.\n\n==Curriculum==\n[[File:Yeshivat HaHesder Yeruham Old Building.jpg|thumb|Lunch room of the Yeshiva]]\nYeshivat HaHesder Yerucham emphasizes the importance of learning [[Talmud]] in depth, specifically through applying the [[Brisker method|Brisker Method]]. A typical day in Yeshiva will include two sessions of intensive Talmud study (''iyun'') and one of extensive study (''bekiut''). \n\nShachris at the Yeshiva is at 6:30am, followed by halachah seder until 8:00am. Breakfast is from 8:00am-8:30am. After breakfast is morning seder, which is typically gemara iyun, and it goes from 8:30am-1:00pm. Following morning seder is lunch and a break from 1:00pm-3pm. Mincha is at 3:00pm, followed by afternoon seder, from about 3:20pm-7:30pm. Afternoon seder consists of more iyun gemara, followed by a couple hours of emmunah. Many of the students use the entire afternoon seder for learning machshava, tanach, mussar, and emmunah. From 7:30pm-8:00pm is Maariv, followed by supper from 8:00pm-8:30pm. Night seder consists of learning bekiut, and it goes from 8:30pm until at least 11:00pm, although there is no given time for night seder to end, and many students learn until much later.[[File:Hayeshiva.jpg|thumb|Lunch room of the Yeshiva]]'''Daily Schedule''': \n\nShachrit: 6:30am-8:00am\n\nBreakfast: 8:00am-8:30am\n\nMorning seder: 8:30am-1:00pm\n\nLunch/break: 1:00pm-3:00pm\n\nMincha: 3:00pm-3:20pm\n\nAfternoon seder: 3:20pm-7:30pm\n\nSupper: 7:30pm-8:00pm\n\nMarriv: 8:00pm-8:30pm \n\nNight seder: 8:30pm-11:00pm (or later)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/26/46/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|last=|first=|date=|website=www.yhy.co.il|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of the afternoon seder, the yeshiva guides its students to base their perspective upon the teachings of [[Yehuda Halevi|Rabbi Yehuda Halevi]] and the [[Judah Loew ben Bezalel|Maharal of Prague]] in accordance with the ideology of [[Abraham Isaac Kook]], as is often customary in Religious Zionist yeshivas. With the goal of educating students to deal independently with the challenges they face living as an observant Jews in modern time in mind, the yeshiva encourages a broader study of Biblical, rabbinic, and other classical and modern sources. Hence, the yeshiva curriculum contains weekly classes in [[Tanakh]], [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Hasidic philosophy]], and the works of Jewish scholars such as [[Maimonides]], [[Nachmanides]], [[Moshe Chaim Luzzatto]], [[Joseph B. Soloveitchik]], [[Abraham Isaac Kook]] and many more.\n\n==Educational approach==\nThe yeshiva educates its students to be aware of their surroundings and attentive to the needs of society in general. The yeshiva believes that the keys to solving Israel\u2019s socioeconomic gaps lie in integration and education. All the students volunteer in the community mainly in the field of education. Many of the yeshiva's alumni settle in Yeruham instead of heading to the country's central cities.\n\nThe yeshiva also promotes other programs, among them:\n* ''Ye'adim'' (goals) - Concern of the Ethiopian Jewry in Israel's situation led Yerucham students to create a leadership training program for Ethiopian students with the intention of their returning to their communities. During the 5 years of Hesder the students synchronize their full Yeshiva studies with a [[Bachelor of Education|B.Ed.]] degree in [[Herzog College]].\n* Young Study Partners - First and second year students dedicate 2 hours weekly to studying Torah subjects with children from the local elementary school. They also serve as positive role models for the local youth and look to form a connection with their families.\n* Charity Fund - The goal of the Fund is to help the needy of Yeruham become self-sufficient and better managers of their money. The Fund uses the cooperation of the local welfare and professional financial advisors to this end.\n* ''B'levav Shalem'' Yeshiva High School \u2013 Because of the lack of high quality religious high schools in the [[Negev]], and as a part of the integration program the Hesder Yeshiva believes in, it was decided by alumni, residents of Yerucham, to open a Yeshiva High School for the local and general population.\n\n==Educational staff==\n[[File:\u05d4\u05e8\u05d1 \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2.JPG|thumb|Rabbi Blumenzweig]]\nIn addition to [[:he:\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5_\u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2|Rabbi Blumenzweig]], the other rabbis who teach in the Yeshiva are  Rabbi [[Uriel Eitam]], Rabbi Chaim Wolfson, Rabbi Shai Gnizi, Rabbi Shmuel Gleizer, Rabbi Achiya Ben Pazi, Rabbi Shmuel Ariel and Rabbi Elyakim Sharir<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/33/51/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd - \u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>. Rabbi Gnizi, Rabbi Gleizer, and Rabbi Ben Pazi all  began as students in the yeshiva. There are also rabbis who come from afar to give weekly classes, such as Rabbi Eliyahu Bazak, Rabbi Meir Kahana. Previously there were other teachers who have since left. These include [[:he:\u05de\u05d9\u05db\u05d0\u05dc \u05d0\u05d1\u05e8\u05d4\u05dd|Rabbi Dr. Michael Abraham]], Rabbi Ehud Barzilai, Rabbi Yair Ya'acobi (who is now serving as the rosh yeshiva of yerucham's relgious highschool \"balbash\"), Rabbi Avi Luria, Rabbis Yoseph Elitzor, and Rabbi Nir Weinberg (who left to establish and head the Hazor'im Yeshiva High-School in the lower Galilee)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/33/51/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd - \u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hesder]]\n*[[Yeshiva]]\n*[[Yerucham]] \n*[[Torah]] \n*[[Israel]] \n*[[Gemara]]\n*[[Brisker method]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.yhy.co.il Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham] (Hebrew)\n*[http://beyachad.dsites.co.il/HTMLs/Home.aspx Midreshet Beyahad] (Hebrew)\n\n==Yeshiva's publications==\nHere are a some of the publications from the yeshivas collective student body that have come out over the past number of years: \n\n*''Kutanot Or'' (Coats of Light) - \"A Jewish Perspective on the meaning of [[modesty]] and its value\", collection of essays edited by Yeshiva's students.\n*''Mimidbar Matana'' (A Present From The Desert) - A monthly newsletter which is sent out to students in the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] and alumni.\n*''Meisharim'' (Righteous) - A journal of articles on a variety of Torah topics, written by the students and teachers, published annually by the Yeshiva.\n*''Hahazit ShebaOref'' (The Home-Front Front) - A collection of essays dealing with the trials and challenges of a non-combat soldier. The book\u2019s intention is to answer some of the questions that soldiers serving in non-field units, such as the importance of their service, and [[Halakha|halakhic]] perspective on different situations.\n\nMany of the rabbis that teach in the yeshiva have also published a number of sefarim. {{Orthodox yeshivot in Israel}}{{Coord|30.9853882|N|34.9274340|E|source:hewiki_region:IL_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title}}[[Category:Yeshivot hesder|Yerucham]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Israel]]\n\n== Bibliography ==\n<references responsive=\"0\" />\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeshivat_Hesder_Yerucham}}\n", "name_user": "Avishai Lightstone", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yeshivat_HaHesder_Yerucham"}
{"title_page": "Harold G. Schrier", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Harold Schrier\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1916|10|17}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1971|6|3|1916|10|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Corder, Missouri]]\n| death_place   = [[Bradenton, Florida]]\n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| nickname      = \n| allegiance    = {{USA}}\n| branch        = {{Flag|United States Marine Corps}}\n| serviceyears  = 1936\u20131957\n| rank          = [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|20px]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]]\n| commands      = \n| unit          = \n| battles       = '''[[World War II]]'''\n*[[Battle of Midway]]\n*[[Battle of Guadalcanal]]\n*[[Battle of New Georgia]]\n*[[Battle of Bougainville]]\n*[[Battle of Iwo Jima]]\n'''[[Korean War]]'''\n*[[Battle of Pusan Perimeter]]\n*[[Battle of Inchon]]\n*[[Battle of Chosin Reservoir]]\n| awards        = [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]]<br/>[[Silver Star Medal]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] w/ [[Combat \"V\"]]<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] w/ Combat \"V\"<br/>[[Purple Heart Medal]]<br />[[Combat Action Ribbon]] (2)\n| laterwork     = \n}}\n\n'''Harold George Schrier''' (October 17, 1916 \u2013 June 3, 1971) was a [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] who served in [[World War II]] and the [[Korean War]]. During the [[Battle of Iwo Jima]], he was awarded the [[Navy Cross]] for leading a 40-man patrol to the top of [[Mount Suribachi]], where he helped raise the first of two [[United States]] [[Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima#Raising the first flag|flag]]s on February 23, 1945. He was wounded in [[North Korea]] during the [[Battle of Chosin Reservoir]] while commanding a rifle company.\n\nThe first flag flown over the southern end of Iwo Jima was regarded to be too small to be seen by the thousands of Marines fighting on the other side of the mountain where the Japanese airfields and most of their troops were located, so it was replaced the same day with a larger flag. Although there were photographs taken of the first flag flying on Mount Suribachi and some which include Schrier, there was no photograph taken of Marines raising the first flag. Schrier was also photographed near the second flag after it was raised. The [[Raising the flag on Iwo Jima|second-flag raising]] has generally been portrayed as the only flag-raising on Mount Suribachi ever since the famous photograph of it which was taken by [[Associated Press]] combat photographer [[Joe Rosenthal]], appeared in the newspapers.<ref>https://www.pulitzer.org/article/joe-rosenthal-and-flag-raising-iwo-jima</ref>\n\nIn 1949, Schrier appeared as himself in the war movie \"Sands of Iwo Jima\", where he hands the American flag to actor [[John Wayne]] (as Sergeant Stryker).\n\nThe [[Marine Corps War Memorial]] in [[Arlington, Virginia]], is modeled after the historic photograph of the second-flag raising and depicts the six flag raisers. \n\n==Early years==\nSchrier was born in [[Corder, Missouri]], on October 17, 1916. He attended high school in [[Lexington, Missouri]].\n\nHe was a yanky doodle flag waver in second battalion marine corp A patch\n\n==U.S. Marine Corps career==\nSchrier enlisted in the Marine Corps on November 12, 1936. After [[United States Marine Corps Recruit Training|recruit training]] at the [[Marine Corps Recruit Depot San Diego|Marine Corps Recruit Depot]] in [[San Diego, California]], he was sent to China as a [[US Embassy]] guard in [[Beijing]]. He also served in [[Tientsin Incident|Tientsin]] and [[Shanghai]]. In August 1940, he became a [[Drill Instructor#U.S. Marine Corps|drill instructor]] at the [[Marine Corps Recruit Depot San Diego]].\n\n===World War II===\nIn early 1942, Schrier joined the 2nd [[Marine Raider]] Battalion at [[Marine Corps Recruit Depot San Diego|Camp Elliott, San Diego]], being promoted to [[platoon sergeant]] in April 1942. In June 1942, he was part of two 2nd Raider Battalion companies that were sent to [[Battle of Midway|Midway Island]] to bolster the garrison there. He participated in the [[Battle of Guadalcanal]] and found himself taking part in the 2nd Marine Raider Battalion's epic [[Carlson's patrol|\"Long Patrol\"]] behind enemy lines from November to December 1942. During this action, he distinguished himself by leading part of his cut off company to safety after his company commander erroneously led them into a hostile situation. In early 1943, he was promoted to [[second lieutenant]] in the field. Subsequently, he was detached to other duties within the Raider organization, such as observation and reconnaissance on enemy-held islands before larger units made assault landings. He was awarded the [[Legion of Merit]] for his work at [[Vangunu|Vangunu Island]] during the [[New Georgia Campaign]] in June 1943. He also served at [[Bougainville Campaign|Bougainville]] in support of military actions there. In February 1944, after the Marine Raiders were disbanded, he returned to the United States to become an [[infantry]] instructor at [[Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton]]. He was assigned next to be the executive officer of E Company, [[2nd Battalion, 28th Marine Regiment]], [[5th Marine Division]]. In September, the 5th Division left Camp Pendleton for [[Hawaii]], for further training. In January 1945, the 5th Division left Hawaii for the assault and capture of Iwo Jima.\n\n====Iwo Jima====\n[[File:Iwo Jima Suribachi DN-SD-03-11845.JPEG|thumb|right|Mount Suribachi on Iwo Jima]]\nOn February 19, 1945, Lt. Schrier and E Company landed with the fifth assault wave on the southeast beach of Iwo Jima closest to Mount Suribachi, which was the [[28th Marine Regiment]]'s objective. Because of heavy fighting, the base of Mount Suribachi was not reached and surrounded until February 22.\n[[File:First Iwo Jima Flag Raising.jpg|220px|thumb|Marine Staff Sergeant [[Louis R. Lowery|Lou Lowery]]'s photo of the first U.S flag flown on [[Mount Suribachi]].<br /> Left to right: 1st. Lt. Harold Schrier (left side of radioman), Pfc. [[Raymond Jacobs]] (radioman), Sgt. [[Henry Oliver Hansen|Henry \"Hank\" Hansen]] (soft cap, holding flagstaff), Platoon Sgt. [[Ernest Ivy Thomas, Jr.]] (seated), Pvt. Phil Ward (holding lower flagstaff), PhM2c. [[John Bradley (United States Navy)|John Bradley]], USN (standing above Ward, holding flagstaff), Pfc. [[James Michels]] (holding [[M1 carbine]]), and Cpl. [[Charles W. Lindberg]] (standing above Michels).]]\n\n====First flag raising====\nOn February 23, 1945, Lieutenant Colonel Chandler Johnson, commander of the [[2nd Battalion, 28th Marine Regiment]], ordered a platoon-size patrol to climb up 556-foot Mount Suribachi. Captain Dave Severance, E Company's commander, assembled the remainder of his Third Platoon and other members of the battalion headquarters, including two Navy [[Hospital corpsman|corpsmen]] and stretcher bearers. First Lieutenant [[Harold G. Schrier#Navy Cross|Harold Schrier]], E Company's executive officer, volunteered for the mission and was handed the Second Battalion's American flag from Lt. Colonel Johnson (or the battalion adjutant) measuring 28 by 54 inches (137 by 71&nbsp;cm), which had been taken from the attack transport {{USS|Missoula|APA-211}} on the way to Iwo Jima by First Lieutenant George G. Wells, the Second Battalion's adjutant in charge of the battalion's flags.<ref>\"The Man Who Carried the Flag on Iwo Jima\", by G. Greeley Wells, New York Times, October 17, 1991, p. A-26</ref> Lt. Schrier was to take a patrol with the flag up the mountain and raise the flag if possible at the summit to signal that Mount Suribachi was captured. At 8:30&nbsp;a.m., Lt. Schrier started climbing with the patrol up the mountain. Less than an hour later, the patrol, after receiving occasional Japanese sniper fire, reached the rim of the volcano. After a brief firefight there, Lt. Schrier and his men captured the summit.\n\nA long section of a Japanese steel water pipe was found on the mountain and the battalion's flag was tied on to it by Lt. Schrier, Sgt. [[Henry Oliver Hansen|Henry Hansen]] and Cpl. [[Charles W. Lindberg|Charles Lindberg]] (Platoon Sergeant [[Ernest Ivy Thomas, Jr.|Ernest Thomas]] was watching inside the group with a grenade in his hand while Pvt. Phil Ward held the bottom of the pipe horizontally off the ground). The flagstaff was then carried to the highest part on the crater and raised by Lt. Schrier, Platoon Sgt. Thomas, Sgt. Hansen,<ref>http://tracesofwar.com/persons/33229/Schrier-Harold-George.htm</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=[[Associated Press]] |first= |date=February 25, 1945 |title=Florida Man Raised Flag on Summit of Suribachi |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/02/25/archives/florida-man-raised-flag-on-summit-of-suribachi.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref><ref>[http://ruralfloridaliving.blogspot.com/2012/07/famous-floridian-friday-ernest-ivy.html] Rural Florida Living. CBS Radio interview by Dan Pryor with flag raiser Ernest \"Boots\" Thomas on February 25, 1945 aboard the [[USS Eldorado (AGC-11)]].</ref> and Cpl. Lindberg<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YXAmygEACAAJ&dq=iwo+jima+monuments&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizoKDi66DoAhUMvJ4KHRNLBmUQ6AEwAXoECAQQAg|title=Iwo Jima Monuments, The Untold Story |last=Brown|first=Rodney |year=2019|publisher=War Museum|accessdate=1 April 2020|isbn=978-1-7334294-3-6}}</ref>at approximately 10:30&nbsp;a.m.<ref>Bradley, J. Powers, R. ''Flags of Our Fathers'': Heroes of Iwo Jima''.</ref> Seeing the [[national colors]] flying caused loud cheering with some gunfire from the Marines, sailors, and Coast Guardsmen on the beach below and from the men on the ships near and docked at the beach. Due to the strong wind on Mount Suribachi, Sgt. Hansen, Pvt. Ward, and Third Platoon [[Hospital corpsman|corpsman]] [[John Bradley (United States Navy)|John Bradley]] helped make the flagstaff stay in a vertical position. The men at, around, and holding the flagstaff, which included Schrier's radioman [[Raymond Jacobs]] (assigned to patrol from F Company), were photographed several times by Staff Sgt. [[Louis R. Lowery]], a photographer with [[Leatherneck magazine|''Leatherneck'' magazine]] who accompanied the patrol up the mountain.<ref name = \"Closing In\">[http://www.nps.gov/wapa/indepth/extContent/usmc/pcn-190-003131-00/sec4a.htm#flag Closing In: Marines in the Seizure of Iwo Jima], by Colonel Joseph H. Alexander, USMC (Retired), 1994, from the [[National Park Service]].</ref><ref name = \"Iwo Jima\">[http://www.iwojima.com/raising/lflagi.gif Picture of the first flag raising]</ref> A firefight with some Japanese soldiers took place, and an enemy grenade caused Sgt. Lowery to fall several feet down the side of the crater, damaging his camera but not his film. \n\nOn February 24, Lt. Schrier ordered Platoon Sgt. Thomas to report early the next morning to Marine Lieutenant General [[Holland Smith]] aboard Navy Vice Admiral [[Richmond K. Turner]]'s [[flagship]] the [[USS Eldorado (AGC-11)]] about the flag raising on Mount Suribachi. On February 25, Platoon Sgt. Thomas met with the two officers and during a CBS radio news interview aboard ship, he named Lt. Schrier, Sgt. Henry Hansen, and himself as the actual flag-raisers.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://ruralfloridaliving.blogspot.com/2012/07/famous-floridian-friday-ernest-ivy.html] Rural Florida Living. CBS Radio interview by Dan Pryor with flag raiser Ernest \"Boots\" Thomas on February 25, 1945 aboard the [[USS Eldorado (AGC-11)]]: \"''Three of us actually raised the flag''\"</ref> Rosenthal's photograph of the second flag raising appeared in the newspapers the same day as Platoon Sgt. Thomas's interview.\n\nLt. Schrier was awarded the Navy Cross for extraordinary heroism on February 23. Platoon Sgt. Thomas was killed on March 3<ref>[http://ruralfloridaliving.blogspot.com/2012/07/famous-floridian-friday-ernest-ivy.html] Rural Florida Living. CBS Radio interview by Dan Pryor with flag raiser Ernest \"Boots\" Thomas on February 25, 1945 aboard the [[USS Eldorado (AGC-11)]].</ref> and Sgt. Hansen was killed on March 1.\n\n====Second flag raising====\n[[File:Moments after the second flag raising, February 1945.jpg|200px|left|thumb|Marine Private Robert Campbell's photo of the two flags on Mt. Suribachi (Lt. Schrier, far left).]]\n[[File:USMC-00932.jpg|thumb|Lt. Schrier (third from left) in [[Joe Rosenthal]]'s \"Gung Ho\" photo]]\nOn the same day that his battalion's flag was raised, Lt. Col. Johnson determined that a larger flag should replace it. The flag was too small to be seen on the other side of the mountain where three Japanese airfields and most of the Japanese troops were located, and Johnson thought that the thousands of Marines fighting there needed the inspiration from seeing the flag. A 96 by 56 inch flag was obtained from a ship docked on shore and brought up to the top of Mount Suribachi by Pfc. [[Rene Gagnon]] the Second Battalion's runner (messenger) for E Company. At the same time, Sgt. [[Michael Strank]], Cpl. [[Harlon Block]], Pfc. [[Franklin Sousley]], and Pfc. [[Ira Hayes]] from Second Platoon, E Company, were sent to take communication wire or supplies up to the Third Platoon and raise the second flag. Once on top, the flag was attached to another Japanese steel pipe. Shortly before 1&nbsp;p.m., Lt. Schrier ordered the second flag raised and the first flag lowered. The four Marines and Pfc. [[Harold Schultz]]<ref name=\"marines.mil\">[http://www.marines.mil/News/News-Display/Article/810457/usmc-statement-on-iwo-jima-flagraisers/ USMC Statement on Marine Corps Flag Raisers], Office of U.S. Marine Corps Communication, 23 June 2016</ref> and Pfc. [[Harold Keller]] (both members Lt. Schrier's patrol)<ref> https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/warrior-iconic-iwo-jima-flag-raising-photo-was-misidentified-marines-n1064766</ref> raised the larger flag. The first flagstaff was lowered by three Marines and Pfc. Gagnon, who removed the flag and took it down the mountain to the battalion adjutant.<ref name=\"Investigating Iwo\">{{cite book |editor-last=Robertson |editor-first=Breanne |date=2019 |title=Investigating Iwo: The Flag Raisings in Myth, Memory, and Esprit de Corps |url=https://www.usmcu.edu/Portals/218/Investigating%20Iwo_WEB3.pdf |location=Quantico, Virginia |publisher=Marine Corps History Division |pages=243, 312 |isbn=978-0-16-095331-6 }}</ref>\n\nThe Marines who captured Mount Suribachi and those who raised the first flag generally did not receive national recognition even though the first flag raising had received some public recognition first. The [[Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima|black and white photograph of the second flag raising]] by [[Joe Rosenthal]] of the [[Associated Press]] became world-famous after appearing in the newspapers as the flag raising on Iwo Jima.  Marine combat photographer Sergeant [[Bill Genaust|William Genaust]], who had accompanied Rosenthal and Marine photographer Pvt. Robert Campbell up Mount Suribachi, filmed the second flag raising in color and it was used in [[newsreel]]s.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">You Tube, Smithsonian Channel, 2008 Documentary (Genaust films) \"Shooting Iwo Jima\" [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JOy6yRAB6BY] Retrieved April 1, 2020</ref> Other combat photographers ascended the mountain after the first flag was raised and the mountaintop secured. These photographers including Rosenthal and an army photographer who was assigned to cover Marine amphibious landings for [[Yank, the Army Weekly|Yank Magazine]], took photos of Marines (including Sgt. Hansen), corpsmen, and themselves around both of the flags. The second flag-raisers received national recognition. After the replacement flag was raised, sixteen Marines, including Schrier and Hansen, and two Navy corpsmen ([[John Bradley (United States Navy)|John Bradley]] and Gerald Ziehme from the 40-man patrol) posed together for Rosenthal around the base of the flagstaff.\n\nOn February 27, Schrier left Mount Suribachi and became the commander of D Company, 2nd Battalion, 28th Marines. He was later awarded the [[Silver Star|Silver Star Medal]] for leading a successful counterattack on March 24 against a large number of fanatical Japanese soldiers who attacked the rear position of his lightly manned command post.\n\nOn March 14, another American flag was officially raised up a flagpole by two Marines under the orders of Lt. Gen. Holland Smith during a ceremony at the [[V Amphibious Corps]] command post on the other side of Mount Suribachi where the [[3rd Marine Division (United States)|3rd Marine Division]] troops were located. The flag flying on the summit of Mount Suribachi since February 23 was taken down. On March 26, 1945, the island was considered secure and the battle of Iwo Jima was officially ended. Lt. Schrier and the 28th Marines left Iwo Jima on March 27 and returned to Hawaii to the 5th Marine Division training camp. Lt. Col. Johnson was killed in action on March 2, Sgt. Genaust was killed on March 4, Sgt. Strank and Cpl. Block were killed on March 1, and Pfc. Sousley was killed on March 21.\n\nLt. Schrier served in San Diego from July to October 1945. Afterwards, he served in [[Seal Beach, California]], [[Samar]], [[Philippines]], and in [[United States Fleet Activities Yokosuka|Yokosuka]], [[Japan]]. In 1949, Captain Schrier returned to the United States and was assigned as a technical advisor (he also appeared as himself with flag raiser Ira Hayes and former corpsman John Bradley) in the motion picture ''[[Sands of Iwo Jima]]'', starring John Wayne.\n\n===Korean War===\nThe [[Korean War]] broke out on June 25, 1950, and Captain Schrier was sent to Korea with the [[1st Provisional Marine Brigade]] in July. He was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] for his actions while serving as the brigade adjutant in August and September during the [[Battle of Pusan Perimeter]] in [[South Korea]]. He was assigned next as the company commander of I Company, [[3rd Battalion, 5th Marines]], [[1st Marine Division]]. During the [[Battle of Chosin Reservoir]] in [[North Korea]], he was wounded in the neck on December 1, during an all-night hill fight at Hill 1520 with Chinese Communist troops. He was evacuated to Japan.\n\n=== Marine Corps War Memorial ===\n[[File:USMC War Memorial Night.jpg|thumb|right|The [[USMC War Memorial|U.S. Marine Corps War Memorial]] in [[Arlington, Virginia|Arlington]], [[Virginia]]]]\n\nThe [[Marine Corps War Memorial]] (also known as the Iwo Jima Memorial) in Arlington, Virginia, which was inspired by Joe Rosenthal's photograph of the second flag-raising on Mount Suribachi by six Marines on February 23, 1945, was dedicated on November 10, 1954 (179th anniversary of the Marine Corps).<ref>[http://www.barracks.marines.mil/History/MarineCorpsWarMemorial.aspx Marine Corps War Memorial] Marine Barracks Washington, D.C.</ref> Schrier, Charles Lindberg, and Lou Lowery, from the patrol that raised the first flag on Mount Suribachi, attended the dedication ceremony as guests.\n\n[[President of the United States|President]] [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] sat upfront during the dedication ceremony with [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Richard Nixon]], [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charles E. Wilson]], [[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense|Deputy Secretary of Defense]] [[Robert B. Anderson|Robert Anderson]], [[Deputy Secretary of the Interior|Assistant Secretary of the Interior]] Orme Lewis, and General [[Lemuel C. Shepherd]], the 20th [[Commandant of the Marine Corps|Commandant]] of the Marine Corps.<ref name=mhmd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vgwrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jZoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4987%2C3731941 |newspaper=Reading Eagle|location=Pennsylvania|agency=Associated Press|title=Memorial honoring Marines dedicated |date=November 10, 1954|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YXAmygEACAAJ&dq=iwo+jima+monuments&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizoKDi66DoAhUMvJ4KHRNLBmUQ6AEwAXoECAQQAg|title=Iwo Jima Monuments, The Untold Story |last=Brown|first=Rodney |year=2019|publisher=War Museum|accessdate=29 March 2020|isbn=978-1-7334294-3-6}}</ref> Ira Hayes, one of the three surviving flag raisers depicted on the monument, was also seated upfront with John Bradley (incorrectly identified as a flag raiser until 2016),<ref>[http://www.marines.mil/News/News-Display/Article/810457/usmc-statement-on-iwo-jima-flagraisers/ USMC Statement on Marine Corps Flag Raisers], Office of U.S. Marine Corps Communication, 23 June 2016</ref> Rene Gagnon (incorrectly identified as a flag raiser until October 16, 2019),<ref name=mhmd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vgwrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jZoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4987%2C3731941 |newspaper=Reading Eagle|location=Pennsylvania|agency=Associated Press|title=Memorial honoring Marines dedicated |date=November 10, 1954|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Warrior in iconic Iwo Jima flag-raising photo was misidentified, Marines Corps acknowledges|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/warrior-iconic-iwo-jima-flag-raising-photo-was-misidentified-marines-n1064766|publisher=NBC News|date=2019-10-16|accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> Mrs Martha Strank, Mrs. Ada Belle Block, and Mrs. Goldie Price (mother of Franklin Sousley).<ref name=mhmd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vgwrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jZoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4987%2C3731941 |newspaper=Reading Eagle|location=Pennsylvania|agency=Associated Press|title=Memorial honoring Marines dedicated |date=November 10, 1954|page=1}}</ref> Those giving remarks at the dedication included Robert Anderson, Chairman of Day; Colonel J.W. Moreau, U.S. Marine Corps (Retired), President, Marine Corps War Memorial Foundation; General Shepherd, who presented the memorial to the American people; [[Felix de Weldon]], sculptor; and Richard Nixon, who gave the dedication address.<ref name=hpdrms>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cPNXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mfYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5563%2C2418577 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |agency=Associated Press |title=Marine monument seen as symbol of hopes, dreams |date=November 10, 1954 |page=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YXAmygEACAAJ&dq=iwo+jima+monuments&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizoKDi66DoAhUMvJ4KHRNLBmUQ6AEwAXoECAQQAg|title=Iwo Jima words:Monuments, The Untold Story |last=Brown|first=Rodney |year=2019|publisher=War Museum|accessdate=29 March 2020|isbn=978-1-7334294-3-6}}</ref> Inscribed on the memorial are the following words:\n\n:In Honor And Memory Of The Men of The United States Marine Corps Who Have Given Their Lives To Their Country Since 10 November 1775\n\n=== Retirement and death ===\nSchrier was promoted to major in May 1951, and was the officer in charge of the Marine Corps recruiting station in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. Afterwards, he was the  [[provost marshal]] at the Marine Corps Recruit Depot, San Diego, California. He retired from the Marine Corps as a [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] in 1957.\n\nSchrier died at a hospital in [[Bradenton, Florida]], in 1971. He is buried in Mansion Memorial Park in [[Ellenton, Florida]].\n\n==Military awards==\nSchrier's military decorations and awards include:\n\n{| align=\"center\"\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|ribbon=Navy Cross ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=award-star|ribbon=Silver_Star_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=award-star|other_device=v|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|other_device=v|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|ribbon=Purple Heart ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Combat_Action_Ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=United States Navy Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|ribbon=U.S._Marine_Corps_Good_Conduct_Medal_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|ribbon=China_Service_Medal_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|other_device=|ribbon=American Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=American Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=5|type=service-star|ribbon=Asiatic-Pacific Campaign ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=World War II Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=Korean_Service_Medal_-_Ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|ribbon=Presidential_Unit_Citation_(Korea).svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=United Nations Service Medal Korea ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Republic of Korea War Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|}\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n|[[Navy Cross]]\n|[[Silver Star]]\n|[[Legion of Merit]]<br />w/ [[Combat \"V\"]] \n|-\n|[[Bronze Star]]<br />w/ Combat \"V\"\n|[[Purple Heart]]\n|[[Combat Action Ribbon]]<br />w/ one {{frac|5|16}}\" Gold Star\n|-\n|[[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Navy and Marine Corps Presidential Unit Citation]]<br /> w/ three [[service star|{{frac|3|16}}\" Bronze Stars]]\n|[[Good Conduct Medal (United States)#Marine Corps Good Conduct Medal|Marine Corps Good Conduct Medal]]\n|[[China Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[American Defense Service Medal]]\n|[[American Campaign Medal]]\n|[[Asiatic-Pacific Campaign Medal]]<br />w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" Silver Star\n|-\n|[[World War II Victory Medal]]\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]]\n|[[Korean Service Medal]]<br />w/ three {{frac|3|16}}\" Bronze Stars\n|-\n|[[Presidential Unit Citation (Korea)|Republic of Korea Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|[[United Nations Korea Medal]]\n|[[Korean War Service Medal|Republic of Korea War Service Medal]]\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Navy Cross citation===\n[[File:Navycross.jpg|left|50px]]\n{{quotation|The President of the United States takes pleasure in presenting the NAVY CROSS to<br /><br /><center>FIRST LIEUTENANT HAROLD G. SCHRIER<br />UNITED STATES MARINE CORPS</center>\nfor service as set forth in the following<br /><br /> \nCITATION:<br /><br />\n   \"For extraordinary heroism as Executive Officer of Company E, Second Battalion, Twenty-Eighth Marines, Fifth Marine Division, in action against enemy Japanese forces on Iwo Jima, Volcano Islands, on 23 February 1945. On the morning of 23 February when his combat team had advanced to the base of Mount Suribachi after four days of severe fighting, First Lieutenant SCHRIER volunteered to lead a forty-man patrol up the steep slopes of the mountain. Quickly organizing his patrol and placing himself at its head, he began the tortuous climb up the side of the volcano, followed by his patrol in single file. Employing the only known approach, an old Japanese trail, he swiftly pushed on until, covered by all the supporting weapons of his battalion, he gained the top of the mountain despite hostile small arms and artillery fire. Forced to engage the remaining enemy in a sharp fire fight, he overcame them without loss in his patrol and occupied the rim of the volcano. Although still under enemy sniper fire, First Lieutenant SCHRIER, assisted by his Platoon Sergeant, raised the National Colors over Mount Suribachi, planting the flagstaff firmly on the highest knoll overlooking the crater, the first American flag to fly over any land in the inner defenses of the Japanese Empire. His inspiring leadership, courage and determination in the face of overwhelming odds upheld the highest traditions of the United States Naval Service.\"\n<center>For the President,<br />JOHN L. SULLIVAN<br />Secretary of the Navy}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeofheroes.com/valor/1_Citations/03_wwii-nc/nc_06wwii_usmcR.html\n|accessdate=2007-01-18\n|title=Navy Cross Awards to members of the U.S. Marines in World War II\n|publisher=HomeofHeroes.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060923113814/http://www.homeofheroes.com/valor/1_Citations/03_wwii-nc/nc_06wwii_usmcR.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-09-23}}</ref>\n\n===Silver Star Citation===\n\nSilver Star Medal\n\nThe President of the United States of America takes pleasure in presenting the Silver Star Medal to First Lieutenant Harold George Schrier, United States Marine Corps, for conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity as Commanding Officer of Company D, Second Battalion, Twenty-eighth Marines, Fifth Marine Division, in action against enemy Japanese forces on Iwo Jima, Volcano Islands, on 24 March 1945. Realizing the seriousness of the situation when a group of approximately one hundred Japanese infiltrated through the main defensive positions shortly after midnight and launched a fanatical attack against the rear of his lightly-manned command post, First Lieutenant Schrier boldly rallied his men and opposed the onrushing enemy, setting a courageous example. His leadership and fighting spirit throughout this action were in keeping with the highest traditions of the United States Naval Service. For the President, John L. Sullivan, Secretary of the Navy\n\n===Legion of Merit===\n\nAwarded for actions during the World War II\n\nThe President of the United States of America takes pleasure in presenting the Legion of Merit to Second Lieutenant Harold George Schrier (MCSN: 0-19234), United States Marine Corps, for exceptionally meritorious conduct in the performance of outstanding services to the Government of the United States as a member of a reconnaissance party attached to the First Marine Raider Regiment operating in the Solomon Islands Area from 13 to 30 June 1943. Preceding the landing of our invasion forces, Second Lieutenant Schrier with his party made his way by canoe to the enemy-held Vangunu Island and for two days, in the face of extreme danger, stayed close to the hostile lines in order to observe troop concentrations, bivouac areas, possible gun positions and trails. When the other members of his party left, he dauntlessly remained in the Japanese-infested area and nine days later flashed signals to the approaching ships and guided troops to the beach. By his fearless devotion to duty in supplying accurate and vital information to the commanding officers, Second Lieutenant Schrier contributed materially to the capture of the area and upheld the highest traditions of the United States Naval Service.\nGeneral Orders: Heroes U.S. Marine Corps, 1861 \u2013 1955: Jane Blakeney\nAction Date: June 13 \u2013 30, 1943\nService: Marine Corps\nRank: Second Lieutenant\nRegiment: 1st Marine Raider Regiment\n\nhttp://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=8139\n\n==Portrayal in films==\n* [[Sands of Iwo Jima]], 1949 (Capt. Harold G. Schrier, USMC as Lieutenant Harold Schrier, USMC).\n* [[Flags of Our Fathers (film)|Flags of Our Fathers]], 2006 (Lieutenant Schrier, USMC, was played by actor [[Jason Gray-Stanford]]).\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|World War II|Biography}}\n*[[Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima]]\n*[[Battle of Iwo Jima]]\n*[[Marine Corps War Memorial]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0775387|name=Harold G. Schrier}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schrier, Harold George}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps officers]]\n[[Category:Battle of Iwo Jima]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Star]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:People from Lafayette County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:People from Bradenton, Florida]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Harold Schrier\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1916|10|17}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1971|6|3|1916|10|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Corder, Missouri]]\n| death_place   = [[Bradenton, Florida]]\n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| nickname      = \n| allegiance    = {{USA}}\n| branch        = {{Flag|United States Marine Corps}}\n| serviceyears  = 1936\u20131957\n| rank          = [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|20px]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]]\n| commands      = \n| unit          = \n| battles       = '''[[World War II]]'''\n*[[Battle of Midway]]\n*[[Battle of Guadalcanal]]\n*[[Battle of New Georgia]]\n*[[Battle of Bougainville]]\n*[[Battle of Iwo Jima]]\n'''[[Korean War]]'''\n*[[Battle of Pusan Perimeter]]\n*[[Battle of Inchon]]\n*[[Battle of Chosin Reservoir]]\n| awards        = [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]]<br/>[[Silver Star Medal]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] w/ [[Combat \"V\"]]<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] w/ Combat \"V\"<br/>[[Purple Heart Medal]]<br />[[Combat Action Ribbon]] (2)\n| laterwork     = \n}}\n\n'''Harold George Schrier''' (October 17, 1916 \u2013 June 3, 1971) was a [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] who served in [[World War II]] and the [[Korean War]]. During the [[Battle of Iwo Jima]], he was awarded the [[Navy Cross]] for leading a 40-man patrol to the top of [[Mount Suribachi]], where he helped raise the first of two [[United States]] [[Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima#Raising the first flag|flag]]s on February 23, 1945. He was wounded in [[North Korea]] during the [[Battle of Chosin Reservoir]] while commanding a rifle company.\n\nThe first flag flown over the southern end of Iwo Jima was regarded to be too small to be seen by the thousands of Marines fighting on the other side of the mountain where the Japanese airfields and most of their troops were located, so it was replaced the same day with a larger flag. Although there were photographs taken of the first flag flying on Mount Suribachi and some which include Schrier, there was no photograph taken of Marines raising the first flag. Schrier was also photographed near the second flag after it was raised. The [[Raising the flag on Iwo Jima|second-flag raising]] has generally been portrayed as the only flag-raising on Mount Suribachi ever since the famous photograph of it which was taken by [[Associated Press]] combat photographer [[Joe Rosenthal]], appeared in the newspapers.<ref>https://www.pulitzer.org/article/joe-rosenthal-and-flag-raising-iwo-jima</ref>\n\nIn 1949, Schrier appeared as himself in the war movie \"Sands of Iwo Jima\", where he hands the American flag to actor [[John Wayne]] (as Sergeant Stryker).\n\nThe [[Marine Corps War Memorial]] in [[Arlington, Virginia]], is modeled after the historic photograph of the second-flag raising and depicts the six flag raisers. \n\n==Early years==\nSchrier was born in [[Corder, Missouri]], on October 17, 1916. He attended high school in [[Lexington, Missouri]].\n\n==U.S. Marine Corps career==\nSchrier enlisted in the Marine Corps on November 12, 1936. After [[United States Marine Corps Recruit Training|recruit training]] at the [[Marine Corps Recruit Depot San Diego|Marine Corps Recruit Depot]] in [[San Diego, California]], he was sent to China as a [[US Embassy]] guard in [[Beijing]]. He also served in [[Tientsin Incident|Tientsin]] and [[Shanghai]]. In August 1940, he became a [[Drill Instructor#U.S. Marine Corps|drill instructor]] at the [[Marine Corps Recruit Depot San Diego]].\n\n===World War II===\nIn early 1942, Schrier joined the 2nd [[Marine Raider]] Battalion at [[Marine Corps Recruit Depot San Diego|Camp Elliott, San Diego]], being promoted to [[platoon sergeant]] in April 1942. In June 1942, he was part of two 2nd Raider Battalion companies that were sent to [[Battle of Midway|Midway Island]] to bolster the garrison there. He participated in the [[Battle of Guadalcanal]] and found himself taking part in the 2nd Marine Raider Battalion's epic [[Carlson's patrol|\"Long Patrol\"]] behind enemy lines from November to December 1942. During this action, he distinguished himself by leading part of his cut off company to safety after his company commander erroneously led them into a hostile situation. In early 1943, he was promoted to [[second lieutenant]] in the field. Subsequently, he was detached to other duties within the Raider organization, such as observation and reconnaissance on enemy-held islands before larger units made assault landings. He was awarded the [[Legion of Merit]] for his work at [[Vangunu|Vangunu Island]] during the [[New Georgia Campaign]] in June 1943. He also served at [[Bougainville Campaign|Bougainville]] in support of military actions there. In February 1944, after the Marine Raiders were disbanded, he returned to the United States to become an [[infantry]] instructor at [[Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton]]. He was assigned next to be the executive officer of E Company, [[2nd Battalion, 28th Marine Regiment]], [[5th Marine Division]]. In September, the 5th Division left Camp Pendleton for [[Hawaii]], for further training. In January 1945, the 5th Division left Hawaii for the assault and capture of Iwo Jima.\n\n====Iwo Jima====\n[[File:Iwo Jima Suribachi DN-SD-03-11845.JPEG|thumb|right|Mount Suribachi on Iwo Jima]]\nOn February 19, 1945, Lt. Schrier and E Company landed with the fifth assault wave on the southeast beach of Iwo Jima closest to Mount Suribachi, which was the [[28th Marine Regiment]]'s objective. Because of heavy fighting, the base of Mount Suribachi was not reached and surrounded until February 22.\n[[File:First Iwo Jima Flag Raising.jpg|220px|thumb|Marine Staff Sergeant [[Louis R. Lowery|Lou Lowery]]'s photo of the first U.S flag flown on [[Mount Suribachi]].<br /> Left to right: 1st. Lt. Harold Schrier (left side of radioman), Pfc. [[Raymond Jacobs]] (radioman), Sgt. [[Henry Oliver Hansen|Henry \"Hank\" Hansen]] (soft cap, holding flagstaff), Platoon Sgt. [[Ernest Ivy Thomas, Jr.]] (seated), Pvt. Phil Ward (holding lower flagstaff), PhM2c. [[John Bradley (United States Navy)|John Bradley]], USN (standing above Ward, holding flagstaff), Pfc. [[James Michels]] (holding [[M1 carbine]]), and Cpl. [[Charles W. Lindberg]] (standing above Michels).]]\n\n====First flag raising====\nOn February 23, 1945, Lieutenant Colonel Chandler Johnson, commander of the [[2nd Battalion, 28th Marine Regiment]], ordered a platoon-size patrol to climb up 556-foot Mount Suribachi. Captain Dave Severance, E Company's commander, assembled the remainder of his Third Platoon and other members of the battalion headquarters, including two Navy [[Hospital corpsman|corpsmen]] and stretcher bearers. First Lieutenant [[Harold G. Schrier#Navy Cross|Harold Schrier]], E Company's executive officer, volunteered for the mission and was handed the Second Battalion's American flag from Lt. Colonel Johnson (or the battalion adjutant) measuring 28 by 54 inches (137 by 71&nbsp;cm), which had been taken from the attack transport {{USS|Missoula|APA-211}} on the way to Iwo Jima by First Lieutenant George G. Wells, the Second Battalion's adjutant in charge of the battalion's flags.<ref>\"The Man Who Carried the Flag on Iwo Jima\", by G. Greeley Wells, New York Times, October 17, 1991, p. A-26</ref> Lt. Schrier was to take a patrol with the flag up the mountain and raise the flag if possible at the summit to signal that Mount Suribachi was captured. At 8:30&nbsp;a.m., Lt. Schrier started climbing with the patrol up the mountain. Less than an hour later, the patrol, after receiving occasional Japanese sniper fire, reached the rim of the volcano. After a brief firefight there, Lt. Schrier and his men captured the summit.\n\nA long section of a Japanese steel water pipe was found on the mountain and the battalion's flag was tied on to it by Lt. Schrier, Sgt. [[Henry Oliver Hansen|Henry Hansen]] and Cpl. [[Charles W. Lindberg|Charles Lindberg]] (Platoon Sergeant [[Ernest Ivy Thomas, Jr.|Ernest Thomas]] was watching inside the group with a grenade in his hand while Pvt. Phil Ward held the bottom of the pipe horizontally off the ground). The flagstaff was then carried to the highest part on the crater and raised by Lt. Schrier, Platoon Sgt. Thomas, Sgt. Hansen,<ref>http://tracesofwar.com/persons/33229/Schrier-Harold-George.htm</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=[[Associated Press]] |first= |date=February 25, 1945 |title=Florida Man Raised Flag on Summit of Suribachi |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/02/25/archives/florida-man-raised-flag-on-summit-of-suribachi.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref><ref>[http://ruralfloridaliving.blogspot.com/2012/07/famous-floridian-friday-ernest-ivy.html] Rural Florida Living. CBS Radio interview by Dan Pryor with flag raiser Ernest \"Boots\" Thomas on February 25, 1945 aboard the [[USS Eldorado (AGC-11)]].</ref> and Cpl. Lindberg<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YXAmygEACAAJ&dq=iwo+jima+monuments&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizoKDi66DoAhUMvJ4KHRNLBmUQ6AEwAXoECAQQAg|title=Iwo Jima Monuments, The Untold Story |last=Brown|first=Rodney |year=2019|publisher=War Museum|accessdate=1 April 2020|isbn=978-1-7334294-3-6}}</ref>at approximately 10:30&nbsp;a.m.<ref>Bradley, J. Powers, R. ''Flags of Our Fathers'': Heroes of Iwo Jima''.</ref> Seeing the [[national colors]] flying caused loud cheering with some gunfire from the Marines, sailors, and Coast Guardsmen on the beach below and from the men on the ships near and docked at the beach. Due to the strong wind on Mount Suribachi, Sgt. Hansen, Pvt. Ward, and Third Platoon [[Hospital corpsman|corpsman]] [[John Bradley (United States Navy)|John Bradley]] helped make the flagstaff stay in a vertical position. The men at, around, and holding the flagstaff, which included Schrier's radioman [[Raymond Jacobs]] (assigned to patrol from F Company), were photographed several times by Staff Sgt. [[Louis R. Lowery]], a photographer with [[Leatherneck magazine|''Leatherneck'' magazine]] who accompanied the patrol up the mountain.<ref name = \"Closing In\">[http://www.nps.gov/wapa/indepth/extContent/usmc/pcn-190-003131-00/sec4a.htm#flag Closing In: Marines in the Seizure of Iwo Jima], by Colonel Joseph H. Alexander, USMC (Retired), 1994, from the [[National Park Service]].</ref><ref name = \"Iwo Jima\">[http://www.iwojima.com/raising/lflagi.gif Picture of the first flag raising]</ref> A firefight with some Japanese soldiers took place, and an enemy grenade caused Sgt. Lowery to fall several feet down the side of the crater, damaging his camera but not his film. \n\nOn February 24, Lt. Schrier ordered Platoon Sgt. Thomas to report early the next morning to Marine Lieutenant General [[Holland Smith]] aboard Navy Vice Admiral [[Richmond K. Turner]]'s [[flagship]] the [[USS Eldorado (AGC-11)]] about the flag raising on Mount Suribachi. On February 25, Platoon Sgt. Thomas met with the two officers and during a CBS radio news interview aboard ship, he named Lt. Schrier, Sgt. Henry Hansen, and himself as the actual flag-raisers.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://ruralfloridaliving.blogspot.com/2012/07/famous-floridian-friday-ernest-ivy.html] Rural Florida Living. CBS Radio interview by Dan Pryor with flag raiser Ernest \"Boots\" Thomas on February 25, 1945 aboard the [[USS Eldorado (AGC-11)]]: \"''Three of us actually raised the flag''\"</ref> Rosenthal's photograph of the second flag raising appeared in the newspapers the same day as Platoon Sgt. Thomas's interview.\n\nLt. Schrier was awarded the Navy Cross for extraordinary heroism on February 23. Platoon Sgt. Thomas was killed on March 3<ref>[http://ruralfloridaliving.blogspot.com/2012/07/famous-floridian-friday-ernest-ivy.html] Rural Florida Living. CBS Radio interview by Dan Pryor with flag raiser Ernest \"Boots\" Thomas on February 25, 1945 aboard the [[USS Eldorado (AGC-11)]].</ref> and Sgt. Hansen was killed on March 1.\n\n====Second flag raising====\n[[File:Moments after the second flag raising, February 1945.jpg|200px|left|thumb|Marine Private Robert Campbell's photo of the two flags on Mt. Suribachi (Lt. Schrier, far left).]]\n[[File:USMC-00932.jpg|thumb|Lt. Schrier (third from left) in [[Joe Rosenthal]]'s \"Gung Ho\" photo]]\nOn the same day that his battalion's flag was raised, Lt. Col. Johnson determined that a larger flag should replace it. The flag was too small to be seen on the other side of the mountain where three Japanese airfields and most of the Japanese troops were located, and Johnson thought that the thousands of Marines fighting there needed the inspiration from seeing the flag. A 96 by 56 inch flag was obtained from a ship docked on shore and brought up to the top of Mount Suribachi by Pfc. [[Rene Gagnon]] the Second Battalion's runner (messenger) for E Company. At the same time, Sgt. [[Michael Strank]], Cpl. [[Harlon Block]], Pfc. [[Franklin Sousley]], and Pfc. [[Ira Hayes]] from Second Platoon, E Company, were sent to take communication wire or supplies up to the Third Platoon and raise the second flag. Once on top, the flag was attached to another Japanese steel pipe. Shortly before 1&nbsp;p.m., Lt. Schrier ordered the second flag raised and the first flag lowered. The four Marines and Pfc. [[Harold Schultz]]<ref name=\"marines.mil\">[http://www.marines.mil/News/News-Display/Article/810457/usmc-statement-on-iwo-jima-flagraisers/ USMC Statement on Marine Corps Flag Raisers], Office of U.S. Marine Corps Communication, 23 June 2016</ref> and Pfc. [[Harold Keller]] (both members Lt. Schrier's patrol)<ref> https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/warrior-iconic-iwo-jima-flag-raising-photo-was-misidentified-marines-n1064766</ref> raised the larger flag. The first flagstaff was lowered by three Marines and Pfc. Gagnon, who removed the flag and took it down the mountain to the battalion adjutant.<ref name=\"Investigating Iwo\">{{cite book |editor-last=Robertson |editor-first=Breanne |date=2019 |title=Investigating Iwo: The Flag Raisings in Myth, Memory, and Esprit de Corps |url=https://www.usmcu.edu/Portals/218/Investigating%20Iwo_WEB3.pdf |location=Quantico, Virginia |publisher=Marine Corps History Division |pages=243, 312 |isbn=978-0-16-095331-6 }}</ref>\n\nThe Marines who captured Mount Suribachi and those who raised the first flag generally did not receive national recognition even though the first flag raising had received some public recognition first. The [[Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima|black and white photograph of the second flag raising]] by [[Joe Rosenthal]] of the [[Associated Press]] became world-famous after appearing in the newspapers as the flag raising on Iwo Jima.  Marine combat photographer Sergeant [[Bill Genaust|William Genaust]], who had accompanied Rosenthal and Marine photographer Pvt. Robert Campbell up Mount Suribachi, filmed the second flag raising in color and it was used in [[newsreel]]s.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">You Tube, Smithsonian Channel, 2008 Documentary (Genaust films) \"Shooting Iwo Jima\" [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JOy6yRAB6BY] Retrieved April 1, 2020</ref> Other combat photographers ascended the mountain after the first flag was raised and the mountaintop secured. These photographers including Rosenthal and an army photographer who was assigned to cover Marine amphibious landings for [[Yank, the Army Weekly|Yank Magazine]], took photos of Marines (including Sgt. Hansen), corpsmen, and themselves around both of the flags. The second flag-raisers received national recognition. After the replacement flag was raised, sixteen Marines, including Schrier and Hansen, and two Navy corpsmen ([[John Bradley (United States Navy)|John Bradley]] and Gerald Ziehme from the 40-man patrol) posed together for Rosenthal around the base of the flagstaff.\n\nOn February 27, Schrier left Mount Suribachi and became the commander of D Company, 2nd Battalion, 28th Marines. He was later awarded the [[Silver Star|Silver Star Medal]] for leading a successful counterattack on March 24 against a large number of fanatical Japanese soldiers who attacked the rear position of his lightly manned command post.\n\nOn March 14, another American flag was officially raised up a flagpole by two Marines under the orders of Lt. Gen. Holland Smith during a ceremony at the [[V Amphibious Corps]] command post on the other side of Mount Suribachi where the [[3rd Marine Division (United States)|3rd Marine Division]] troops were located. The flag flying on the summit of Mount Suribachi since February 23 was taken down. On March 26, 1945, the island was considered secure and the battle of Iwo Jima was officially ended. Lt. Schrier and the 28th Marines left Iwo Jima on March 27 and returned to Hawaii to the 5th Marine Division training camp. Lt. Col. Johnson was killed in action on March 2, Sgt. Genaust was killed on March 4, Sgt. Strank and Cpl. Block were killed on March 1, and Pfc. Sousley was killed on March 21.\n\nLt. Schrier served in San Diego from July to October 1945. Afterwards, he served in [[Seal Beach, California]], [[Samar]], [[Philippines]], and in [[United States Fleet Activities Yokosuka|Yokosuka]], [[Japan]]. In 1949, Captain Schrier returned to the United States and was assigned as a technical advisor (he also appeared as himself with flag raiser Ira Hayes and former corpsman John Bradley) in the motion picture ''[[Sands of Iwo Jima]]'', starring John Wayne.\n\n===Korean War===\nThe [[Korean War]] broke out on June 25, 1950, and Captain Schrier was sent to Korea with the [[1st Provisional Marine Brigade]] in July. He was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] for his actions while serving as the brigade adjutant in August and September during the [[Battle of Pusan Perimeter]] in [[South Korea]]. He was assigned next as the company commander of I Company, [[3rd Battalion, 5th Marines]], [[1st Marine Division]]. During the [[Battle of Chosin Reservoir]] in [[North Korea]], he was wounded in the neck on December 1, during an all-night hill fight at Hill 1520 with Chinese Communist troops. He was evacuated to Japan.\n\n=== Marine Corps War Memorial ===\n[[File:USMC War Memorial Night.jpg|thumb|right|The [[USMC War Memorial|U.S. Marine Corps War Memorial]] in [[Arlington, Virginia|Arlington]], [[Virginia]]]]\n\nThe [[Marine Corps War Memorial]] (also known as the Iwo Jima Memorial) in Arlington, Virginia, which was inspired by Joe Rosenthal's photograph of the second flag-raising on Mount Suribachi by six Marines on February 23, 1945, was dedicated on November 10, 1954 (179th anniversary of the Marine Corps).<ref>[http://www.barracks.marines.mil/History/MarineCorpsWarMemorial.aspx Marine Corps War Memorial] Marine Barracks Washington, D.C.</ref> Schrier, Charles Lindberg, and Lou Lowery, from the patrol that raised the first flag on Mount Suribachi, attended the dedication ceremony as guests.\n\n[[President of the United States|President]] [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] sat upfront during the dedication ceremony with [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Richard Nixon]], [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charles E. Wilson]], [[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense|Deputy Secretary of Defense]] [[Robert B. Anderson|Robert Anderson]], [[Deputy Secretary of the Interior|Assistant Secretary of the Interior]] Orme Lewis, and General [[Lemuel C. Shepherd]], the 20th [[Commandant of the Marine Corps|Commandant]] of the Marine Corps.<ref name=mhmd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vgwrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jZoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4987%2C3731941 |newspaper=Reading Eagle|location=Pennsylvania|agency=Associated Press|title=Memorial honoring Marines dedicated |date=November 10, 1954|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YXAmygEACAAJ&dq=iwo+jima+monuments&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizoKDi66DoAhUMvJ4KHRNLBmUQ6AEwAXoECAQQAg|title=Iwo Jima Monuments, The Untold Story |last=Brown|first=Rodney |year=2019|publisher=War Museum|accessdate=29 March 2020|isbn=978-1-7334294-3-6}}</ref> Ira Hayes, one of the three surviving flag raisers depicted on the monument, was also seated upfront with John Bradley (incorrectly identified as a flag raiser until 2016),<ref>[http://www.marines.mil/News/News-Display/Article/810457/usmc-statement-on-iwo-jima-flagraisers/ USMC Statement on Marine Corps Flag Raisers], Office of U.S. Marine Corps Communication, 23 June 2016</ref> Rene Gagnon (incorrectly identified as a flag raiser until October 16, 2019),<ref name=mhmd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vgwrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jZoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4987%2C3731941 |newspaper=Reading Eagle|location=Pennsylvania|agency=Associated Press|title=Memorial honoring Marines dedicated |date=November 10, 1954|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Warrior in iconic Iwo Jima flag-raising photo was misidentified, Marines Corps acknowledges|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/warrior-iconic-iwo-jima-flag-raising-photo-was-misidentified-marines-n1064766|publisher=NBC News|date=2019-10-16|accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> Mrs Martha Strank, Mrs. Ada Belle Block, and Mrs. Goldie Price (mother of Franklin Sousley).<ref name=mhmd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vgwrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jZoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4987%2C3731941 |newspaper=Reading Eagle|location=Pennsylvania|agency=Associated Press|title=Memorial honoring Marines dedicated |date=November 10, 1954|page=1}}</ref> Those giving remarks at the dedication included Robert Anderson, Chairman of Day; Colonel J.W. Moreau, U.S. Marine Corps (Retired), President, Marine Corps War Memorial Foundation; General Shepherd, who presented the memorial to the American people; [[Felix de Weldon]], sculptor; and Richard Nixon, who gave the dedication address.<ref name=hpdrms>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cPNXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mfYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5563%2C2418577 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |agency=Associated Press |title=Marine monument seen as symbol of hopes, dreams |date=November 10, 1954 |page=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YXAmygEACAAJ&dq=iwo+jima+monuments&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizoKDi66DoAhUMvJ4KHRNLBmUQ6AEwAXoECAQQAg|title=Iwo Jima words:Monuments, The Untold Story |last=Brown|first=Rodney |year=2019|publisher=War Museum|accessdate=29 March 2020|isbn=978-1-7334294-3-6}}</ref> Inscribed on the memorial are the following words:\n\n:In Honor And Memory Of The Men of The United States Marine Corps Who Have Given Their Lives To Their Country Since 10 November 1775\n\n=== Retirement and death ===\nSchrier was promoted to major in May 1951, and was the officer in charge of the Marine Corps recruiting station in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. Afterwards, he was the  [[provost marshal]] at the Marine Corps Recruit Depot, San Diego, California. He retired from the Marine Corps as a [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] in 1957.\n\nSchrier died at a hospital in [[Bradenton, Florida]], in 1971. He is buried in Mansion Memorial Park in [[Ellenton, Florida]].\n\n==Military awards==\nSchrier's military decorations and awards include:\n\n{| align=\"center\"\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|ribbon=Navy Cross ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=award-star|ribbon=Silver_Star_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=award-star|other_device=v|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|other_device=v|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|ribbon=Purple Heart ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Combat_Action_Ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=United States Navy Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|ribbon=U.S._Marine_Corps_Good_Conduct_Medal_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|ribbon=China_Service_Medal_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|other_device=|ribbon=American Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=American Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=5|type=service-star|ribbon=Asiatic-Pacific Campaign ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=World War II Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=Korean_Service_Medal_-_Ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|ribbon=Presidential_Unit_Citation_(Korea).svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=United Nations Service Medal Korea ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Republic of Korea War Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|}\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n|[[Navy Cross]]\n|[[Silver Star]]\n|[[Legion of Merit]]<br />w/ [[Combat \"V\"]] \n|-\n|[[Bronze Star]]<br />w/ Combat \"V\"\n|[[Purple Heart]]\n|[[Combat Action Ribbon]]<br />w/ one {{frac|5|16}}\" Gold Star\n|-\n|[[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Navy and Marine Corps Presidential Unit Citation]]<br /> w/ three [[service star|{{frac|3|16}}\" Bronze Stars]]\n|[[Good Conduct Medal (United States)#Marine Corps Good Conduct Medal|Marine Corps Good Conduct Medal]]\n|[[China Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[American Defense Service Medal]]\n|[[American Campaign Medal]]\n|[[Asiatic-Pacific Campaign Medal]]<br />w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" Silver Star\n|-\n|[[World War II Victory Medal]]\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]]\n|[[Korean Service Medal]]<br />w/ three {{frac|3|16}}\" Bronze Stars\n|-\n|[[Presidential Unit Citation (Korea)|Republic of Korea Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|[[United Nations Korea Medal]]\n|[[Korean War Service Medal|Republic of Korea War Service Medal]]\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Navy Cross citation===\n[[File:Navycross.jpg|left|50px]]\n{{quotation|The President of the United States takes pleasure in presenting the NAVY CROSS to<br /><br /><center>FIRST LIEUTENANT HAROLD G. SCHRIER<br />UNITED STATES MARINE CORPS</center>\nfor service as set forth in the following<br /><br /> \nCITATION:<br /><br />\n   \"For extraordinary heroism as Executive Officer of Company E, Second Battalion, Twenty-Eighth Marines, Fifth Marine Division, in action against enemy Japanese forces on Iwo Jima, Volcano Islands, on 23 February 1945. On the morning of 23 February when his combat team had advanced to the base of Mount Suribachi after four days of severe fighting, First Lieutenant SCHRIER volunteered to lead a forty-man patrol up the steep slopes of the mountain. Quickly organizing his patrol and placing himself at its head, he began the tortuous climb up the side of the volcano, followed by his patrol in single file. Employing the only known approach, an old Japanese trail, he swiftly pushed on until, covered by all the supporting weapons of his battalion, he gained the top of the mountain despite hostile small arms and artillery fire. Forced to engage the remaining enemy in a sharp fire fight, he overcame them without loss in his patrol and occupied the rim of the volcano. Although still under enemy sniper fire, First Lieutenant SCHRIER, assisted by his Platoon Sergeant, raised the National Colors over Mount Suribachi, planting the flagstaff firmly on the highest knoll overlooking the crater, the first American flag to fly over any land in the inner defenses of the Japanese Empire. His inspiring leadership, courage and determination in the face of overwhelming odds upheld the highest traditions of the United States Naval Service.\"\n<center>For the President,<br />JOHN L. SULLIVAN<br />Secretary of the Navy}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeofheroes.com/valor/1_Citations/03_wwii-nc/nc_06wwii_usmcR.html\n|accessdate=2007-01-18\n|title=Navy Cross Awards to members of the U.S. Marines in World War II\n|publisher=HomeofHeroes.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060923113814/http://www.homeofheroes.com/valor/1_Citations/03_wwii-nc/nc_06wwii_usmcR.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-09-23}}</ref>\n\n===Silver Star Citation===\n\nSilver Star Medal\n\nThe President of the United States of America takes pleasure in presenting the Silver Star Medal to First Lieutenant Harold George Schrier, United States Marine Corps, for conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity as Commanding Officer of Company D, Second Battalion, Twenty-eighth Marines, Fifth Marine Division, in action against enemy Japanese forces on Iwo Jima, Volcano Islands, on 24 March 1945. Realizing the seriousness of the situation when a group of approximately one hundred Japanese infiltrated through the main defensive positions shortly after midnight and launched a fanatical attack against the rear of his lightly-manned command post, First Lieutenant Schrier boldly rallied his men and opposed the onrushing enemy, setting a courageous example. His leadership and fighting spirit throughout this action were in keeping with the highest traditions of the United States Naval Service. For the President, John L. Sullivan, Secretary of the Navy\n\n===Legion of Merit===\n\nAwarded for actions during the World War II\n\nThe President of the United States of America takes pleasure in presenting the Legion of Merit to Second Lieutenant Harold George Schrier (MCSN: 0-19234), United States Marine Corps, for exceptionally meritorious conduct in the performance of outstanding services to the Government of the United States as a member of a reconnaissance party attached to the First Marine Raider Regiment operating in the Solomon Islands Area from 13 to 30 June 1943. Preceding the landing of our invasion forces, Second Lieutenant Schrier with his party made his way by canoe to the enemy-held Vangunu Island and for two days, in the face of extreme danger, stayed close to the hostile lines in order to observe troop concentrations, bivouac areas, possible gun positions and trails. When the other members of his party left, he dauntlessly remained in the Japanese-infested area and nine days later flashed signals to the approaching ships and guided troops to the beach. By his fearless devotion to duty in supplying accurate and vital information to the commanding officers, Second Lieutenant Schrier contributed materially to the capture of the area and upheld the highest traditions of the United States Naval Service.\nGeneral Orders: Heroes U.S. Marine Corps, 1861 \u2013 1955: Jane Blakeney\nAction Date: June 13 \u2013 30, 1943\nService: Marine Corps\nRank: Second Lieutenant\nRegiment: 1st Marine Raider Regiment\n\nhttp://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=8139\n\n==Portrayal in films==\n* [[Sands of Iwo Jima]], 1949 (Capt. Harold G. Schrier, USMC as Lieutenant Harold Schrier, USMC).\n* [[Flags of Our Fathers (film)|Flags of Our Fathers]], 2006 (Lieutenant Schrier, USMC, was played by actor [[Jason Gray-Stanford]]).\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|World War II|Biography}}\n*[[Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima]]\n*[[Battle of Iwo Jima]]\n*[[Marine Corps War Memorial]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n*{{IMDb name